// AUTO-GENERATED for gi_final from the GI 31-34 + 35-38 delta docs (assemble_gi_final.py). Regenerate, don't hand-edit.

const QUIZ_CONFIG = {"id": "gi_final", "title": "GI Final", "emoji": "🩺"};
const IMAGES = {};
const LO_ANSWERS = {"31_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia.", "why": "E. coli O157:H7 — it causes HUS, and unlike the rest it is made worse by antibiotics, so the stakes of recognizing it are highest."}, "31_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere.", "why": "Blood/leukocytes (inflammatory), stool volume (voluminous = secretory), and fat/odor or response to fasting (osmotic/malabsorptive) sort almost every case."}, "31_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis.", "why": "Secretory — an enterotoxin is actively driving secretion, so the lumen stays wet even without ingested solute; an osmotic diarrhea would have slowed or stopped with fasting."}, "31_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host.", "why": "You choose the single study that confirms a named hypothesis (the red-flag pattern points to it), rather than ordering a broad panel and hoping something turns up."}, "31_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line.", "why": "Glucose drives sodium-coupled absorption (SGLT1) so water is reabsorbed even while the gut secretes; Coca-Cola's glucose-to-sodium ratio is backwards and hyperosmolar, so it pulls water into the lumen instead."}, "33_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope.", "why": "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) presents as maroon stool from below, and unlike most lower sources you can actually stop it endoscopically — so the top is scoped first."}, "33_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both.", "why": "EUS — it stages and biopsies the mass through the gastric wall, assesses vascular involvement and nodes in one step; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling."}, "33_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining.", "why": "Whether liquids get stuck too: solids-only points to a structural narrowing; solids-and-liquids points to a motility disorder (work it up with barium first)."}, "33_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns.", "why": "Diverticulosis — acute, painless, significant hematochezia over 50 that self-limits ~80% of the time; endoscopic therapy for lower bleeds is limited, so management is largely supportive after excluding an upper source."}, "33_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas.", "why": "ERCP — about a 10% complication rate, and its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis from manipulating the shared bile/pancreatic-duct opening."}, "33_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them.", "why": "Colonoscopy is offered FIRST and is the only test that also prevents cancer by removing polyps; a stool test (annual FIT) is for patients who decline colonoscopy — it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}, "35_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar anchors the entire lecture on one picture: the parietal cell and the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump that does the actual work of secreting hydrogen ions into the gastric lumen in exchange for K⁺. Everything you study after this — every drug class — is just a different way of getting at that pump, so it pays to fix the wiring now. Four signals converge on it: three stimulate, one restrains.", "why": "ON: acetylcholine (M3), histamine (H2), and gastrin (CCK-B) all activate kinases that drive the H+/K+-ATPase. DOWN: PGE2 (EP receptors) inhibits secretion and is cytoprotective."}, "35_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the workhorse LO — Parmar marches one class per slide on a fixed template (mechanism / uses / adverse effects), and he is explicit that you should learn the class logic rather than memorize every interchangeable agent. The organizing spine is a potency ladder: antacids neutralize, H2RAs block a receptor, PPIs and PCABs hit the pump itself. Climb the ladder and acid suppression deepens.", "why": "Antacid (transient neutralization) < H2RA (~60-70%, tachyphylaxis) < PPI (>90%, irreversible) < PCAB (reversible K-competition). Signature AEs: Al/Mg bowel shift, cimetidine antiandrogen/CYP, PPI B12-Mg-fracture-C.diff, misoprostol pregnancy CI."}, "35_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The whole point of this LO is one comparison: H2RA versus PPI. Parmar drew the contrast explicitly in numbers, and the exam loves it because the two drugs sit on the same pathway but act at different points — a receptor versus the pump.", "why": "The PPI wins on potency (>90% vs ~60-70%) and durability (irreversible pump block, no tachyphylaxis). The long-term cost is decreased B12 bioavailability, because the acid that normally frees B12 from dietary protein is suppressed."}, "35_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar flagged the interaction material directly — “focus from exam point of view, this is important” — while warning that the full list reads as an unmemorizable laundry. The way through is to sort by mechanism: enzyme inhibition (CYP), a change in gastric pH, and physical binding/chelation. Get the three buckets and any specific pair is predictable.", "why": "CYP inhibition: cimetidine (warfarin/diazepam/eletriptan) and omeprazole/esomeprazole + clopidogrel (CYP2C19). Raised gastric pH: PPIs impairing digoxin/azole absorption. Binding: sucralfate + quinolones, and antacids chelating tetracyclines/iron — space dosing 2-4 h."}, "35_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar time-boxed this to a few minutes but framed it as high-stakes — H. pylori is a common infection linked to peptic ulcer disease and an established risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma and MALT lymphoma. The cancer link is the reason eradication is taken seriously, and the reason the rules tightened in the 2024 guidelines.", "why": "14-day Optimized BQT (PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth) is gold standard; clarithromycin was dropped for resistance, with PCAB-dual and rifabutin-triple as alternatives. After 14 days, confirmation of eradication (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) is mandatory."}, "35_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar builds this whole lecture as a receptor map, so the first move is to learn the categories, not the individual drugs. Nausea and vomiting are integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema and the vomiting center, and four neurotransmitter-receptor pairs feed them: ACh (M1), histamine (H1), substance P (NK1), and serotonin (5-HT3). Each pair has a drug class that blocks it. Two adjunct families — cannabinoids (CB1 agonists) and benzodiazepines (GABA-A modulators) — plus dexamethasone and olanzapine round out the rescue/adjuvant tier.", "why": "ACh/M1 (scopolamine), histamine/H1 (meclizine, dimenhydrinate), substance P/NK1 (the -pitants), and serotonin/5-HT3 (the -setrons) — the four receptors that organize the entire antiemetic toolkit."}, "35_7": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism story is the heart of the lecture, and Parmar tells it as one vomiting-reflex framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema and the vomiting center in the floor of the fourth ventricle, and each antiemetic class simply blocks one input. Get the framework first and every drug's MOA is just \"which receptor does it sit on.\"", "why": "The immediate episode is serotonin acting at 5-HT3 (acute phase) — covered by a setron; the day-3 episode is substance P acting at NK1 (delayed phase) — covered by a -pitant. Highly emetogenic regimens combine both plus dexamethasone."}, "35_8": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Therapeutic uses cluster around a short vocabulary you'll see repeated on every slide — CINV (chemotherapy-induced), PONV (postoperative), RINV (radiation-induced), motion sickness, and gastroparesis. Because the indications overlap so heavily, the exam discriminates by adverse effect: each class has a signature toxicity, and that's where Parmar spends his emphasis.", "why": "Both block D2 and cause EPS, but metoclopramide's boxed warning is irreversible tardive dyskinesia (cap therapy at 12 weeks), while droperidol's is QT prolongation/torsades (mandatory 12-lead ECG before and 2-3 hours after dosing)."}, "35_9": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Two interaction themes carry this LO, and Parmar flags both as testable: the Parkinson's contraindication that follows every dopamine blocker, and the CYP-P450 interactions of the NK1 antagonists — which he ties directly to COMLEX drug-interaction questions after talking to a student who took the exam.", "why": "Aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4, the enzyme that clears dexamethasone, so dexamethasone accumulates and its dose must be reduced; rolapitant inhibits CYP2D6 instead, leaving CYP3A4-mediated dexamethasone metabolism untouched, so no adjustment is needed."}, "37_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rose opens the way an old-school trauma surgeon does: before he lays a hand on the patient he pictures what's going on inside — skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum stripped away, the organs laid bare. The whole lecture rests on this. For trauma the single most useful map is the four quadrants, because the quadrant plus the mechanism tells you which organs are at risk. (The finer nine-region map — epigastric, umbilical, hypogastric, and the paired hypochondriac, lumbar, and iliac regions — is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma.)", "why": "Picturing the organs by quadrant lets the mechanism predict the injury: knowing what is fixed vs mobile, and what sits in the struck quadrant, tells you which organs to look for before any imaging."}, "37_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. If Rose makes one point in this lecture, it is ultrasound: that's the thing that's going to make all the difference. The bedside FAST exam (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) is fast, cheap, repeatable, and increasingly done on a phone probe — he told the class to chase the ultrasound teams in the ED and learn it. FAST hunts for free fluid (blood), air, and gross organ injury in the liver, kidneys, and spleen, and the density of the fluid even distinguishes blood from serous fluid. The volume of blood in the abdomen can be estimated from it.", "why": "Because stability — not the FAST result — drives disposition: the unstable patient is exsanguinating and goes straight to the OR, while the one who responds to crystalloid has bought the time for a CT and a trial of observation."}, "37_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism tells you what to look for, so name it. Blunt / compression (the common one) drives organs against the spine and breaks ribs over the spleen and liver. Penetrating (stab, gunshot) injures along its trajectory — and the trajectory, not just the entry point, is what matters: a wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because the diaphragm rides up to the nipples on expiration. Crush is severe compression (steering wheel, a wall). Iatrogenic injury is caused by us during an operation. Blast injury drives foreign bodies inward and combines penetrating with crush.", "why": "The path determines which organs the object actually crossed; a wound's entry point can be misleading, since a sub-nipple or angled trajectory may cross the diaphragm or track retroperitoneally and spare or strike organs far from the entry site."}, "37_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the heart of the lecture, and the spleen is its center. The spleen is the most frequently injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma and the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its capsule is paper-thin and its attachments (gastrosplenic ligament, attachments to the diaphragm) tear easily. Injury comes from penetrating, blunt, or iatrogenic mechanisms — and isolated splenic injury occurs in only about 30% of cases, so when you find a hurt spleen, look for the stomach, left kidney, pancreas, and ribs too.", "why": "The grade encodes laceration depth and parenchymal/vascular involvement, which is exactly what dictates management: splenic grades I–III can be repaired or observed (especially in stable patients and children, to avoid OPSI), while IV–V — crush, bisection, hilar, or shattered — are not repairable and require splenectomy."}, "37_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rose closes fast and by anecdote, so keep this tight. The pancreas is a crush injury: lying retroperitoneally across the spine, a focal midline blow can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column — his garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine, repaired with a Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy. Work it up with amylase and lipase (also checked in lavage fluid), see it on CT/ultrasound, and use ERCP to define the ductal anatomy; expect severe back pain because there's no room in the retroperitoneum. Thoracoabdominal and pelvic trauma in a crashing multi-trauma patient is a team approach through a thoracoabdominal incision, working chest and abdomen at once.", "why": ""}, "38_1": {"answer": "ANATOMY FIRST. Moljo built the whole lecture around a single ED vignette — a 68-year-old woman with three days of left-lower-quadrant pain, low-grade fever and chills — and her one repeated instruction is to start with anatomy: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Name what lives in the painful quadrant (sigmoid colon, ovary, bladder) and the history questions write themselves. The classic tell is constant LLQ pain with fever; ask too about timing, change in bowel habits, urinary symptoms, and — in a woman — gynecologic causes, which is why she argued the declined pelvic exam still leaves a real gap (an ovarian source can masquerade as colonic pain). Notice the exam targets recognition here, not deep recall — you are pattern-matching a presentation, not memorizing a checklist.", "why": ""}, "38_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The workup runs on one idea Moljo built into a quiz slide: each test answers a specific question, and you order it to confirm a suspicion rather than to fish. The lab panel sorts the differential — CBC (infection? anemia from a GI bleed?), CMP (diabetes, electrolytes, and crucially renal function before contrast), CRP/ESR (inflammation), urinalysis and culture (UTI, the LLQ mimic), HCG (pregnancy in any woman of childbearing age), and blood cultures if she looks septic. Two of those — the CMP renal check and the HCG — exist specifically to make it safe to give contrast.", "why": "Choose a water-soluble contrast medium. If it leaks through a perforation it is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes barium peritonitis — a severe chemical peritonitis."}, "38_3": {"answer": "THE DEFINITIONS LADDER. The whole LO turns on keeping four terms straight, so climb the ladder deliberately. A diverticulum is a single sac-like outpouching of colonic mucosa through a weak point in the muscular wall; diverticula is just the plural. DiverticulOSIS is the presence of diverticula — often asymptomatic. DiverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which is then subdivided into uncomplicated versus complicated (abscess, fistula, obstruction, or free perforation). Diverticular disease is the umbrella term for clinically significant, symptomatic disease — including diverticulitis, diverticular bleeding, and segmental colitis. The exam loves to swap osis and itis on you, so anchor it: -osis = the pouches, -itis = the pouches inflamed.", "why": "Diverticulum = a single colonic outpouching; diverticulosis = their presence (often asymptomatic); diverticulitis = inflammation of one (uncomplicated/complicated); diverticular disease = the symptomatic umbrella. A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum because it herniates only mucosa/submucosa, not all wall layers."}, "38_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — UNCOMPLICATED VS COMPLICATED. Every management decision forks on one split: uncomplicated diverticulitis (inflammation only) is managed medically, often outpatient; complicated disease (abscess, perforation, obstruction, fistula) needs a more aggressive, usually inpatient and sometimes surgical approach. The modern, high-yield shift lives on the uncomplicated side — and the entire complication ladder lives on the other.", "why": "Antibiotics are reserved for complicated disease or high-risk hosts (major comorbidity, immunocompromise, immunomodulating drugs, systemic disturbance). A fluoroquinolone (or TMP-SMX) does not cover anaerobes, so it must be paired with metronidazole; amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone."}};
