const LECTURE_CONTENT = {"31": {"prof": "Cyril Blavo, D.O.", "tldr": "Acute infectious diarrhea is usually self-limited — your job is to classify it (inflammatory vs secretory vs osmotic) and replace fluid and electrolytes, orally first and IV only when oral fails.", "mustKnows": ["Classify before you treat. Split every case into inflammatory (blood + fecal leukocytes + fever; EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter) vs non-inflammatory, then non-inflammatory into secretory (voluminous watery, ETEC/cholera) and osmotic (smaller volume; rotavirus, Giardia, EPEC). The bucket drives the workup and the fluids.", "Secretory diarrhea dehydrates fast. Secretory means an enterotoxin drives active secretion — voluminous watery non-bloody stools that persist even with fasting. ETEC (traveler's) and Vibrio cholerae are the archetypes; patients can lose enough fluid and electrolytes to die without looking 'septic.'", "The one bug you cannot miss: E. coli O157:H7. EHEC O157:H7 makes a Shiga-like cytotoxin → hemolytic uremic syndrome (azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia). Do NOT give antibiotics — they increase HUS risk. Blavo flags HUS as a recurring board question.", "Know the toxin vocabulary. Exotoxins are secreted proteins: enterotoxin (gut — cholera, Staph), neurotoxin (C. botulinum), cytotoxin (C. difficile). Endotoxin is the LPS of gram-negative bacteria, released on cell death. C. diff is a cytotoxin, not a neurotoxin.", "Work up to validate, not to fish. Most diarrhea needs no testing. Work up only red flags (moderate/severe dehydration, bloody or voluminous stool, >48 h, high fever, recent antibiotics, immunocompromised). Calprotectin/lactoferrin beat fecal leukocytes; O&P ×3 for Giardia; osmotic gap >160 = osmotic diarrhea.", "ORS is glucose-sodium cotransport — and it is first-line. Oral rehydration solution works because glucose drags sodium and water across the gut (SGLT1). WHO ORS ≈ 245 mOsm/L, Na 75, glucose 75. Sodas and juices have glucose far exceeding sodium and can worsen losses. Use ORT whenever possible.", "Reserve IV — and avoid the drug traps. IV only when ORT is not feasible (persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk): NS, LR, or D5NS, individualized. Bismuth → Reye syndrome in <17. Antimotility and antiemetics with caution. BRAT diet is obsolete; zinc shortens duration."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Recognize the etiology of common infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TOXIN VOCABULARY. Exotoxins are secreted proteins and come in three flavors the exam keeps straight: enterotoxins act on the gut surface to drive secretion (Vibrio cholerae, Staph aureus); neurotoxins damage nerves (Clostridium botulinum); and cytotoxins damage cells in any tissue (Clostridioides difficile). Endotoxin is different — it is the lipopolysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria (E. coli, Salmonella), released when the organism dies, which is why those infections keep triggering inflammation even as bacteria are killed. Blavo briefly misspoke and corrected himself here, so pin it down: C. difficile is a cytotoxin; C. botulinum is the neurotoxin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "C. difficile makes a cytotoxin; C. botulinum makes a neurotoxin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Endotoxin is the LPS of gram-negative bacteria, released on bacterial death."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ONE YOU CANNOT MISS. Enterohemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC), serotype O157:H7, produces a Shiga-like cytotoxin and is the inflammatory, bloody diarrhea that progresses to hemolytic uremic syndrome — the triad of azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia. Blavo calls HUS out specifically as a recurring board question, and the high-yield twist lives in management: antibiotics increase the risk of HUS, so you withhold them (we return to this in LO 31.5)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "EHEC O157:H7 → Shiga-like cytotoxin → HUS (azotemia, MAHA, thrombocytopenia)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Cytotoxin vs neurotoxin: C. difficile = cytotoxin (colonic mucosa); C. botulinum = neurotoxin (nerves). Blavo misspoke and corrected this in lecture."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reflexively giving antibiotics for \"bacterial\" bloody diarrhea — in O157:H7 they raise HUS risk. Withhold them."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Don't memorize the organism list — bucket every bug as inflammatory, secretory, or osmotic. The bucket drives workup and fluids."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo says you can mostly skip memorizing the organism roll-call — so what is the one organism he tells you never to forget, and why?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Identify the clinical presentations of common infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere."}, {"t": "p", "x": "STOOL TELLS. Bloody, mucoid stool with fecal leukocytes and fever is the inflammatory pattern (mucosal invasion). Voluminous watery non-bloody stool is secretory (ETEC, cholera). Greasy, malodorous stool is the malabsorptive/osmotic picture of Giardia — its trophozoites carpet the mucosa so fat isn't absorbed. And the timing tells too: rotavirus classically causes two to three days of vomiting before the watery diarrhea begins, a sequence Blavo flags as a distinguishing clue."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Greasy, foul-smelling, non-bloody stool points to Giardia (fat malabsorption)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rotavirus: 2-3 days of vomiting before watery diarrhea."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE EXAM IS REALLY A DEHYDRATION EXAM. Blavo closed the first hour on this for a reason: in diarrhea, most of the physical exam is hunting for dehydration. Look for dry mucosa, decreased skin turgor, poor capillary refill, tachycardia, hypotension, sunken eyes, and reduced urine output. In an infant, the pathognomonic pair is the fontanelle: a sunken anterior fontanelle means dehydration; a bulging one means raised intracranial pressure (think meningitis). The exam loves to make you flip those two."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Infant sunken fontanelle = dehydration; bulging = raised ICP."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The infant fontanelle is a two-way sign: sunken → dehydration, bulging → raised ICP. Same anatomy, opposite emergencies."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Secretory = voluminous watery that persists with fasting; osmotic = smaller volume that stops with fasting. Volume + fasting separate them."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "In any diarrhea workup, assess dehydration first — it is the finding that changes your disposition fastest."}, {"t": "q", "x": "What three stool characteristics let you sort a diarrhea into inflammatory, secretory, or osmotic right at the bedside?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Recognize the differential diagnosis of common infectious diarrhea", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SECRETORY / OSMOTIC FORK. The cleanest discriminator is what happens when the patient stops eating. Secretory diarrhea is enterotoxin-driven active secretion — the lumen stays wet whether or not food is present, so it is voluminous and persists with fasting (ETEC, cholera). Osmotic diarrhea depends on an unabsorbed solute pulling water in, so it is smaller-volume and resolves with fasting (rotavirus, EPEC, Giardia). Inflammatory diarrhea sits apart, marked by blood, mucus, and fecal leukocytes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Secretory diarrhea persists with fasting; osmotic diarrhea resolves with it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Inflammatory = blood + fecal leukocytes + fever; non-inflammatory lacks all three."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Type / Stool / Examples / Key tell): Inflammatory — Bloody, mucoid, fecal leukocytes, fever · EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter · Blood + leukocytes ; Secretory — Voluminous watery, non-bloody · ETEC, V. cholerae · Persists with fasting ; Osmotic — Small-volume watery, ± greasy · Rotavirus, Giardia, EPEC · Resolves with fasting"}, {"t": "p", "x": "MECHANISM UNDER THE FORK. Normal absorption runs on coupled transporters — SGLT1 (Na/glucose), NHE3 (Na/H), the DRA Cl⁻/HCO₃⁻ exchanger — and on tight junctions that gate the paracellular path. Toxins tip this balance: secretion up, absorption down. You don't need the molecular detail memorized, but knowing the machinery is why ORS (next LO) even works."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INTEGRATE THE EXPOSURE HISTORY. This is Blavo's \"Cyril Why Blavo\" lesson — the differential is only as good as the targeted questions you ask to collapse it. Travel and stream/well water raise ETEC and Giardia; day-care raises rotavirus and Shigella; recent antibiotics raise C. difficile; undercooked ground beef / fast food raises O157:H7. Generate the broad list, then let one or two intentional questions sort it."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The classification IS the differential: inflammatory vs secretory vs osmotic. Place the case in a bucket and the workup and treatment fall out."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Secretory and osmotic are both non-bloody — separate them by stool volume and the response to fasting, not by blood."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Calling every loose-stool patient \"gastroenteritis\" — it can be IBD/IBS, not infection. The term implies infectious but doesn't prove it."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient has voluminous watery non-bloody diarrhea that doesn't stop when they stop eating. Secretory or osmotic — and what is the reasoning?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Identify the workup of infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PICK THE TEST THAT CONFIRMS A HYPOTHESIS. Stool guaiac finds occult blood; calprotectin / lactoferrin are leukocyte proteins that detect inflammation more reliably than the fecal-leukocyte smear; stool culture & sensitivity targets bacterial causes in severe or high-risk cases; ova & parasites repeated ×3 catches Giardia a single sample misses; a stool osmotic gap >160 mOsm/kg marks osmotic diarrhea; and a urine specific gravity >1.020 with elevated BUN confirms dehydration. Blavo's frame: you order the test that validates a specific suspicion, never a shotgun panel."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Calprotectin / lactoferrin beat fecal leukocytes for detecting gut inflammation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A stool osmotic gap >160 mOsm/kg indicates osmotic diarrhea."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Suspected Giardia: repeat stool O&P ×3 before calling it negative."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Work up only the red flags (bloody/voluminous, severe dehydration, >48 h, fever, recent antibiotics, immunocompromised). Otherwise observe and rehydrate."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Calprotectin and lactoferrin are more reliable than the fecal-leukocyte smear for confirming intestinal inflammation."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Treating one negative O&P as ruling out Giardia — sensitivity is low, so repeat ×3 when the clinical picture fits."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo says a test is run \"to validate what you think, not to find the answer.\" How should that change which stool study you order?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Recognize the management of common infectious diarrheas, including fluid and electrolyte management (ORS, IV)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY ORS WORKS. Oral rehydration solution exploits glucose-coupled sodium cotransport (SGLT1): glucose pulls sodium across the mucosa, and water follows osmotically. That coupling is why ORS must contain both glucose and sodium in balance — the WHO formulation is ~245 mOsm/L, with Na 75 and glucose 75. It also explains why sodas and fruit juices are poor substitutes: their glucose far exceeds their sodium, so the unbalanced osmotic load can actually pull more water into the gut and worsen the diarrhea — Blavo's chart showing Coca-Cola's huge sugar load makes the point."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ORS works by glucose-sodium cotransport (SGLT1) pulling water across the gut."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sodas/juices: glucose ≫ sodium → can worsen diarrheal losses."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN TO REACH FOR IV. Use ORT whenever possible; go intravenous only when ORT is not feasible or appropriate — persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk, or impaired mental status. Note that mild vomiting is NOT a contraindication to ORS. IV options (normal saline, half-normal saline, lactated Ringer's, D5/NS) are individualized to severity and labs; monitor closely and transition back to ORS once the patient is resuscitated."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DRUG TRAPS. Antibiotics are reserved for severe febrile bacterial diarrhea or the immunocompromised — empiric use is not beneficial and can be harmful: they raise HUS risk in O157:H7 and prolong fecal shedding in Salmonella. Use antimotility (loperamide) and antiemetic agents cautiously. Bismuth subsalicylate risks Reye syndrome in patients <17 (it's a salicylate). The BRAT diet is obsolete (too restrictive), while zinc shortens duration and severity."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bismuth subsalicylate risks Reye syndrome in children <17."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "In O157:H7, antibiotics increase HUS risk — withhold them."}, {"t": "key", "x": "ORS = glucose-sodium cotransport. Both ingredients are required; the glucose is what drives the sodium-and-water absorption that rehydrates."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "ORT first, IV only when oral fails (persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk). Mild vomiting alone is not a contraindication."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Empiric antibiotics / antimotility for every diarrhea — harmful in O157:H7 (HUS) and Salmonella (shedding). Treat with fluids, not reflexes."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Why is an ORS containing BOTH glucose and sodium more effective than plain water — and why is Coca-Cola a poor substitute?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Antibiotics for every bacterial diarrhea. The reflex to treat a \"bacterial\" bloody stool backfires in E. coli O157:H7, where antibiotics increase Shiga-toxin release and HUS risk. Treat with fluids. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Secretory = osmotic. Both are non-bloody, but secretory is voluminous and persists with fasting; osmotic is smaller-volume and resolves with fasting. → LO 31.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. \"Vomiting, so no oral fluids.\" Mild vomiting is not a contraindication to ORS; you can still rehydrate orally while the patient vomits a little. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Bismuth in a child. Bismuth subsalicylate is a salicylate → Reye syndrome risk in patients under 17. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Cytotoxin vs neurotoxin. C. difficile makes a cytotoxin; the neurotoxin producer is C. botulinum. → LO 31.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. One negative O&P rules out Giardia. A single ova-and-parasite exam is insensitive — repeat it ×3 when the picture fits. → LO 31.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"bloody diarrhea, stool grows O157:H7\" → withhold antibiotics. Fluids only; antibiotics worsen HUS."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"voluminous watery stools, no blood, rapid dehydration\" → secretory (ETEC/cholera), not osmotic."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"child is vomiting, so mom withheld fluids\" → still give ORS; mild vomiting isn't a contraindication."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"parent gave Pepto-Bismol to a 6-year-old\" → Reye-syndrome risk (salicylate)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"pseudomembranous colitis after antibiotics\" → C. difficile cytotoxin (not a neurotoxin)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"one O&P negative but greasy stools persist\" → repeat O&P ×3 for Giardia."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Oral rehydration & antimotility/antidiarrheal pharmacology — also Lec 41 (Laxative & Antidiarrheal Agents)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Secretory-vs-inflammatory reasoning reappears in the GI-bleed logic — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Infectious vs inflammatory (IBD/IBS) overlap on the differential — revisited in later GI pathology"}]}]}, "33": {"prof": "Jeffrey Schneider, M.D.", "tldr": "Endoscopy is organized by what each scope can see and whether it is diagnostic, therapeutic, or both — and CRC screening (start at 45, colonoscopy offered first) is the single highest-yield piece.", "mustKnows": ["Diagnostic vs therapeutic vs both — tag every scope. EGD and EUS are both; ERCP is therapeutic (you already know the diagnosis); wireless capsule is diagnostic only (it can't biopsy or treat). This single frame answers most procedure questions.", "The #1 cause of a big lower-GI bleed is an upper source. A brisk upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) pumps maroon stool from below. It matters because endoscopic therapy stops upper bleeds (clip the vessel, band varices) but has limited power for lower bleeds — so exclude an upper source first.", "EUS = staging (and deep biopsy). Endoscopic ultrasound stages esophageal, gastric, and pancreatic cancer (absent widespread mets) and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall. It is the answer to \"how do you biopsy the pancreatic mass\" — not percutaneous CT. MRCP is the noninvasive test for common-bile-duct stones.", "ERCP is the most dangerous scope — and it's therapeutic. Since MRCP, ERCP is reserved almost exclusively for therapy (relieve biliary obstruction: stones causing jaundice, gallstone pancreatitis, cholangitis; unblock a malignant duct). Complication rate ~10%; the dreaded one is post-ERCP pancreatitis.", "Barrett's → adenocarcinoma (lower esophagus). Barrett's (salmon mucosa, intestinal metaplasia) is a precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; the upper esophagus gives squamous cell cancer. Surveil q3-5y; don't sit on a PPI for years without a look.", "Dysphagia logic: solids vs solids-and-liquids. Solids only = a structural narrowing (cancer, EoE rings, Schatzki ring). Solids AND liquids = a motility disorder (achalasia) — get a barium study first; endoscopy looks near-normal in motility disorders.", "CRC screening: start 45; colonoscopy first. Average-risk screening starts at 45; colonoscopy q10y is offered FIRST, with annual FIT only if colonoscopy is declined. High-risk (first-degree relative <60, or two first-degree relatives): colonoscopy q5y, starting age 40 or 10 yr before the youngest affected relative.", "Cologuard = detection, not prevention. Cologuard (FIT-DNA) is 92% sensitive for cancer but only 42% for advanced adenomas — so it finds cancer, it doesn't prevent it. Every positive needs a colonoscopy; it is contraindicated in high-risk patients and is not equivalent to colonoscopy."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe the role of endoscopic procedures for GI hemorrhage", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PPI TRICK. Before endoscopy you start an IV proton pump inhibitor. It works not by reducing pain but by clot stability: acutely raising the gastric pH toward neutral lets the platelet clot hold (clot stability = pH + platelets). In places without a gastroenterologist, that is sometimes the only bridge for hours."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "An IV PPI raises gastric pH so the clot holds (clot stability = pH + platelets)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "UPPER IS TREATABLE; LOWER OFTEN IS NOT. The role of endoscopy in a bleed is both diagnostic and therapeutic — but the therapy is far more powerful for upper pathology. A bleeding ulcer with a visible vessel of the gastroduodenal artery gets clipped; esophageal varices (portal hypertension from cirrhosis) get banded. For lower-GI bleeding the endoscopic therapeutic potential is genuinely limited."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE EXAM'S FAVORITE LINE. Schneider repeats it: the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed is an upper GI bleed moving fast. A brisk duodenal ulcer pumps maroon stool from below — and because you can stop an upper source but mostly cannot stop a lower one, you exclude the top first in a big, unstable bleed."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Endoscopic hemostasis works far better for UPPER than LOWER GI bleeds."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A brisk upper source is the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Endoscopy can stop upper bleeds (clip ulcers, band varices) but has limited power for lower bleeds — which is why an upper source is excluded first."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Bleeding workup order: resuscitate (volume ± blood) → IV PPI → endoscopy to diagnose and treat."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Assuming maroon stool = a lower source. A fast duodenal-ulcer bleed presents from below; miss it and you miss the treatable lesion."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient pumps out large-volume maroon stool from below. Why is your first worry an UPPER source — and what does that change about management?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the use of ERCP, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and wireless capsule endoscopy", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Scope / Reaches / sees / Role / Core use): EGD — Mouth → 2nd duodenum · Both · GERD/Barrett's, ulcers, varices ; EUS — Behind stomach: pancreas, CBD, nodes · Both · Staging; biopsy pancreatic mass ; ERCP — Ampulla; bile & pancreatic ducts · Therapeutic · Relieve biliary obstruction ; Capsule — Small bowel · Dx only · Occult small-bowel bleed"}, {"t": "p", "x": "EUS = STAGING (and deep biopsy). Endoscopic ultrasound puts an ultrasound probe on the scope tip, so it sees behind the stomach — the pancreas, common bile duct, vessels, and nodes. Its indication is staging esophageal, gastric, and pancreatic cancer (in the absence of widespread metastases), and it biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall. Schneider's standing case: jaundice plus a pancreatic mass → the answer is EUS, not a percutaneous CT-guided biopsy (which risks tract seeding and undersampling). EUS also analyzes IPMN cyst fluid and diagnoses GISTs (submucosal — a surface biopsy reads normal)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "EUS stages esophageal/gastric/pancreatic cancer and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ERCP = THERAPEUTIC. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists do: a side-viewing scope reaches the ampulla, cuts a sphincterotomy, and pulls out stones. Since MRCP can diagnose noninvasively, ERCP is now reserved almost exclusively for therapy — relieving biliary obstruction (stones causing jaundice, gallstone pancreatitis, or cholangitis; unblocking a malignant duct). It does not diagnose a pancreatic mass."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WCE = DIAGNOSTIC ONLY. Wireless capsule endoscopy is a swallowed camera (the makers named it M2A) for the small bowel beyond scope reach. Its #1 indication is occult GI bleeding with a negative upper and lower endoscopy — it usually finds angiodysplasia / AVMs. It cannot biopsy or treat, you don't know exactly where it is, and it is contraindicated in stricturing Crohn disease (it can lodge and require surgery)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ERCP is therapeutic (relieve obstruction), not diagnostic — MRCP/EUS diagnose."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Capsule endoscopy is diagnostic-only; #1 use is occult small-bowel bleed; avoid in stricturing Crohn."}, {"t": "key", "x": "EUS = staging. It stages and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall in one step — the answer to \"how do you biopsy it?\""}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Sending a pancreatic mass to a radiologist for percutaneous biopsy, or doing ERCP to diagnose it — both wrong. EUS stages and biopsies; ERCP only treats."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Capsule = diagnostic only; ERCP = therapeutic; EGD and EUS = both. Tagging each scope answers most procedure questions."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A jaundiced patient has a pancreatic-head mass and no metastases. Which procedure stages AND biopsies it — and why not just send them to a radiologist?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "List the disease entities and endoscopic findings of the upper gastrointestinal tract", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GERD → BARRETT'S → ADENOCARCINOMA. GERD's mechanism is a loose valve — transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation, not excess acid. Chronic reflux can produce Barrett's: salmon-colored mucosa whose biopsy shows intestinal metaplasia, a precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus. Keep the esophagus's split straight: upper = squamous cell cancer, lower = adenocarcinoma. This is why it's irresponsible to sit on a PPI for years without a look; Barrett's gets surveyed every 3-5 years."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Barrett's (intestinal metaplasia) → adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; upper = squamous."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DYSPHAGIA: ONE HISTORY QUESTION. The discriminator is what gets stuck. Solids only = a structural narrowing — cancer (not in a 30-year-old), eosinophilic esophagitis (concentric rings, atopic patient, frequent food impaction), or a Schatzki ring (a single distal ring, the 'steakhouse' bolus). Solids AND liquids = a motility disorder (achalasia) — and here endoscopy is near-normal, so get a barium study first. Achalasia's birds-beak is a radiographic, not endoscopic, finding."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Solids only = structural narrowing; solids + liquids = motility (barium first)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DYSPEPSIA, AND THE BEST-TEST TRAP. Dyspepsia (bloating, belching, no heartburn) is usually a functional motility issue; scope it when conservative measures fail or alarm features appear. While in there, you can biopsy for H. pylori and celiac disease — but Schneider's repeated burn: endoscopy is NOT the best test for either. Because both are patchy, the noninvasive tests win: urea breath / stool antigen for H. pylori and tissue transglutaminase IgA for celiac, especially to confirm eradication or diagnosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "For H. pylori and celiac, noninvasive tests beat endoscopic biopsy (patchy disease)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Barrett's = adenocarcinoma precursor (lower esophagus, intestinal metaplasia). The esophagus splits: upper squamous, lower adeno."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "EoE = multiple concentric rings in an atopic patient with impactions; Schatzki = a single distal ring. Both cause solid dysphagia."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Calling endoscopic biopsy the best test for H. pylori or celiac — the disease is patchy, so noninvasive tests are better."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient has progressive dysphagia. What single feature of the history tells you to think 'structural' versus 'motility' before any test?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the use of lower endoscopic procedures for the differential diagnosis of the colorectal area", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIVERTICULOSIS vs DIVERTICULITIS — never mix osis and itis. DiverticulOSIS is the #1 cause of acute, painless, hemodynamically significant hematochezia over age 50, and it stops on its own ~80% of the time. DiverticulITIS is the inflamed one — left-lower-quadrant pain and fever, usually without significant bleeding — and colonoscopy is contraindicated in the acute phase. (And the seeds-and-nuts taboo is debunked.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "DiverticulOSIS = painless significant lower bleed (stops ~80%); diverticulITIS = LLQ pain + fever, no bleed."}, {"t": "p", "x": "OTHER LOWER BLEEDS. Angiodysplasia / AVMs weep slowly (often found on capsule); internal hemorrhoids give small-volume bright-red blood; ischemic colitis is painful bloody diarrhea at watershed zones; and colorectal cancer bleeds occultly through the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence — the reason we screen (LO 33.6)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "IBD IS A VISUAL DIAGNOSIS. Schneider's line: \"the diagnosis is more visual than histologic.\" Crohn disease is discontinuous — skip lesions, cobblestoning, aphthous and serpiginous ulcers, anywhere mouth-to-anus. Ulcerative colitis is continuous from the rectum proximally. If you see the word cobblestoning, say Crohn's."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Crohn's = discontinuous skip lesions + cobblestoning; UC = continuous from the rectum."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Mixing diverticulOSIS (painless bleed) and diverticulITIS (LLQ pain, fever, no bleed). Say the wrong one and you get the question wrong."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cobblestoning or skip lesions → Crohn's; continuous from the rectum → ulcerative colitis. IBD is read more by eye than by biopsy."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Acute painless significant hematochezia in the elderly → diverticulosis (stops ~80%); first exclude a fast upper source."}, {"t": "q", "x": "An elderly patient has acute, painless, large-volume hematochezia and is stable. What is the most likely source, and why is endoscopic therapy limited?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Understand the indications and complications of endoscopy", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ERCP is the most dangerous GI scope (~10% complications); the dreaded one is post-ERCP pancreatitis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CONTRAINDICATIONS WORTH KNOWING. Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis (abdominal inflammation — you don't push a scope through it). Wireless capsule is contraindicated in stricturing Crohn disease (it can lodge). General complications across scopes include bleeding and perforation; ERCP adds bleeding from the sphincterotomy and duodenal perforation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis; capsule in stricturing Crohn's."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Forgetting that ERCP — not the bigger-looking colonoscopy — is the highest-risk scope, because of post-ERCP pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Don't scope through inflammation: acute diverticulitis contraindicates colonoscopy; stricturing Crohn's contraindicates the capsule."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The two procedure headlines: ERCP = most dangerous (pancreatitis ~10%); capsule = safest but powerless (diagnostic only, can lodge in a stricture)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Which endoscopic procedure carries the highest complication rate, and what is its signature complication?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "State the colonoscopy and the screening recommendations of the American College of Gastroenterology", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NUMBERS (2022 update). Average-risk screening now starts at 45 (down from 50; African Americans also 45). Colonoscopy every 10 years is offered FIRST; annual FIT is for patients who decline colonoscopy — not an equal menu option. Individualize ages 76-85; stop routine screening by 85 (or earlier when life expectancy is under ~10 years)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Average-risk CRC screening: start 45; colonoscopy q10y offered first; annual FIT if declined."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HIGH-RISK TIMING. A first-degree relative with CRC/advanced adenoma under 60, or two first-degree relatives at any age, makes a patient high-risk: colonoscopy every 5 years, starting at age 40 OR 10 years before the youngest affected relative, whichever is earlier. (Relative diagnosed at 55 → start at 45 by the math, but 40 is earlier, so start 40.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "High-risk: colonoscopy q5y, start 40 or 10 yr before the youngest affected relative."}, {"t": "p", "x": "COLOGUARD — DETECTION, NOT PREVENTION. Cologuard is FIT-DNA (FIT plus a methylated-DNA assay), repeated every 3 years. It is ~92% sensitive for cancer but only ~42% for advanced adenomas — so it finds cancer but doesn't prevent it (you can't remove a polyp through a stool test). Every positive needs a colonoscopy; only ~4% of positives have cancer; and it is contraindicated in high-risk patients. Offer it only to someone refusing colonoscopy — never as an equivalent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cologuard (FIT-DNA, q3y) = 92% cancer / 42% advanced adenoma → detection, not prevention."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Group / Start / Interval / Notes): Average-risk — 45 · Colonoscopy q10y (first) · Annual FIT only if colonoscopy declined ; High-risk — 40, or 10 yr before youngest case · Colonoscopy q5y · FDR <60, or two FDRs ; Cologuard (FIT-DNA) — — · q3y · 92% cancer / 42% adenoma; not high-risk"}, {"t": "key", "x": "Average-risk: start 45, colonoscopy q10y offered first, annual FIT only if declined. High-risk: q5y, start 40 or 10 yr before the youngest case."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Telling a patient a stool test equals colonoscopy — colonoscopy is offered first; FIT/Cologuard are for those who decline, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cologuard = detection, not prevention: great at finding cancer (92%), poor at advanced adenomas (42%), useless in high-risk, and every positive still needs a colonoscopy."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient's primary-care office told them a stool test is an equal alternative to colonoscopy. What is wrong with that, and what should have been said?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. ERCP for diagnosis. ERCP is therapeutic (relieve obstruction); diagnose with EUS / MRCP. With MRCP available, ERCP is reserved for treatment. → LO 33.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. \"Endoscopy is the best test for H. pylori / celiac.\" Both are patchy, so noninvasive tests (urea breath / stool antigen; tTG-IgA) are better. → LO 33.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. DiverticulOSIS = diverticulITIS. OSIS = painless significant bleed; ITIS = LLQ pain + fever, no bleed (and colonoscopy is contraindicated). → LO 33.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Stopping a lower-GI bleed endoscopically. Endoscopic therapy is limited below; upper bleeds you can clip or band. → LO 33.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Barrett's → squamous. Barrett's → adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; squamous is the upper esophagus. → LO 33.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Biopsy a pancreatic mass percutaneously. Use EUS — it stages and biopsies through the stomach wall; percutaneous biopsy risks seeding. → LO 33.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. \"Stool test or colonoscopy — your choice.\" Colonoscopy is offered FIRST; FIT is for those who decline, and Cologuard is not equivalent. → LO 33.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Cologuard for everyone (and high-risk). It is detection-not-prevention, only 42% for advanced adenomas, and contraindicated in high-risk. → LO 33.6"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"we did an ERCP to find out what was going on\" → wrong framing; ERCP treats, EUS/MRCP diagnose."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"scope biopsy was negative for H. pylori, so it's gone\" → confirm with urea breath / stool antigen."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"elderly, painless, large-volume maroon stool, stable\" → diverticulosis (after excluding a fast upper source)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"brisk maroon stool, hypotensive\" → think upper source moving fast (treatable), not just \"lower bleed.\""}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"salmon tongue above the GE junction, years on a PPI\" → Barrett's → adenocarcinoma; surveil q3-5y."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"jaundice + pancreatic-head mass, how do you biopsy?\" → EUS, not percutaneous."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"told the stool test is equivalent to colonoscopy\" → colonoscopy first; FIT only if colonoscopy refused."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"Cologuard was negative, so reassured\" → only 42% for advanced adenomas; detection, not prevention."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — H. pylori testing & acid-suppression pharmacology — also Lec 35 (Drugs for Peptic Ulcers & Gastric Acidity)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Esophageal varices, portal hypertension & cirrhosis — also Lec 39-40 (Chronic Liver Disease)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — ERCP, choledocholithiasis & biliary obstruction — also Lec 44-45 (Pathology / Surgery of the Biliary Tract)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — DiverticulOSIS (bleed) vs diverticulITIS (inflammation) — also Lec 38 (Abdominal Pain / Diverticulitis)"}]}]}, "35": {"prof": "Dr. Mayur Parmar", "tldr": "GI pharmacology by target: acid suppression climbs antacids → H2 blockers → PPIs to H. pylori quadruple therapy; antiemetics block the vomiting-reflex receptors — 5-HT3, dopamine, NK1, histamine.", "mustKnows": ["1. One pump, four switches. Acetylcholine (M3), histamine (H2), and gastrin (CCK-B) all activate protein kinases that drive the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump to secrete acid, while PGE2 is inhibitory and cytoprotective. Every acid drug works by blocking one of these switches or the pump itself.", "2. The acid-suppression ladder. Antacids neutralize acid already present (transient); H2RAs reversibly block H2 and cut acid ~60-70% (best nocturnally, prone to tachyphylaxis); PPIs irreversibly inhibit the pump for >90% suppression (resynthesis ~18-24 h); vonoprazan (PCAB) reversibly blocks the pump's K⁺ site without needing acid activation.", "3. Cimetidine is the interaction drug. Cimetidine is a potent CYP450 inhibitor (↑warfarin, diazepam, eletriptan), has antiandrogenic effects at high dose (gynecomastia / galactorrhea), and can ↑serum creatinine without true renal injury. Famotidine is ~20× more potent, longer-acting, and has far fewer interactions — the preferred H2RA.", "4. PPI + clopidogrel = the CYP2C19 trap. Omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19, which is the enzyme that activates the prodrug clopidogrel — so they blunt its antiplatelet effect and the pair should be avoided. Pantoprazole is the safer PPI when clopidogrel is required.", "5. Four receptors, four classes; acute vs delayed. Vomiting is integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema, driven by four receptor pairs: ACh (M1) → scopolamine; histamine (H1) → meclizine/dimenhydrinate; substance P (NK1) → the -pitants; serotonin (5-HT3) → the -setrons. In CINV, the acute phase is serotonin/5-HT3 (peripheral, <24 h) and the delayed phase is substance P/NK1 (central, days 1-5) — setrons cover acute, -pitants cover delayed.", "6. Meclizine is H1, NOT H2 — the planted trap. Meclizine and dimenhydrinate are H1 antihistamines for motion sickness/vestibular nausea; scopolamine is the M1 antagonist. A stem calling meclizine an \"H2 antagonist\" is a deliberate distractor — H2 blockers are the -tidines for acid suppression. H1/M1 agents are ineffective at the CTZ, so they don't cover CINV.", "7. D2 antagonists → EPS; two different boxed warnings. All D2 antagonists (prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, amisulpride) cause extrapyramidal symptoms. Metoclopramide carries a boxed warning for irreversible tardive dyskinesia — avoid use beyond 12 weeks. Droperidol carries a boxed warning for QT prolongation/torsades, requiring a 12-lead ECG before and 2-3 h after dosing.", "8. All D2 antagonists are contraindicated in Parkinson's. Blocking dopamine worsens a disease defined by dopamine loss, so every D2 antagonist antiemetic is contraindicated in Parkinson's disease — prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, and amisulpride alike. It is the same D2 blockade that produces their EPS."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe the physiology of gastric acid secretion and the cellular targets that regulate it", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar anchors the entire lecture on one picture: the parietal cell and the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump that does the actual work of secreting hydrogen ions into the gastric lumen in exchange for K⁺. Everything you study after this — every drug class — is just a different way of getting at that pump, so it pays to fix the wiring now. Four signals converge on it: three stimulate, one restrains."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE THREE STIMULATORS. Acetylcholine binds M3 muscarinic receptors, histamine (released from nearby ECL cells) binds H2 receptors, and gastrin binds CCK-B (gastrin) receptors. Each receptor, once bound, activates protein kinases that switch on the proton pump — so the three pathways are parallel inputs to one output. That parallel wiring is exactly why a histamine blocker only gets you partway: shut off H2 and you still have ACh and gastrin driving the pump. The exam's favorite move here is to swap the receptor subtypes — histamine is H2, not H1; gastrin is CCK-B, not CCK-A."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Parietal-cell stimulators: ACh→M3, histamine→H2, gastrin→CCK-B, all → the proton pump."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE INHIBITORY ARM. Prostaglandin E2 is the counterweight: it binds parietal-cell EP receptors to inhibit acid secretion while it boosts mucus, bicarbonate, and mucosal blood flow — the cytoprotective package. Hold onto this, because it pays off twice downstream: it is why NSAIDs (which knock out protective prostaglandins) cause ulcers, and why the PGE1 analog misoprostol can prevent them. PGE2 is the only one of the four that turns acid down."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PGE2 is inhibitory + cytoprotective (mucus, HCO₃, blood flow) — the opposite of the other three."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Every acid drug maps onto this one diagram: antacids neutralize the product, H2RAs block H2, PPIs/PCAB hit the pump, misoprostol mimics PGE2. Learn the wiring once."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Histamine acts at H2 (not H1) and gastrin at CCK-B (not CCK-A) on the parietal cell — the subtype swap is the classic distractor."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Three parallel ON switches (ACh, histamine, gastrin) feed one pump — which is why blocking the pump itself (PPI) beats blocking any single upstream receptor."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Four molecules regulate the parietal cell. Three turn acid ON and one turns it DOWN — name each, its receptor, and which way it pushes."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the agents used to treat peptic ulcers and gastric acidity and their adverse effects", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the workhorse LO — Parmar marches one class per slide on a fixed template (mechanism / uses / adverse effects), and he is explicit that you should learn the class logic rather than memorize every interchangeable agent. The organizing spine is a potency ladder: antacids neutralize, H2RAs block a receptor, PPIs and PCABs hit the pump itself. Climb the ladder and acid suppression deepens."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ANTACIDS — NEUTRALIZE, DON'T SUPPRESS. These are weak bases that react with gastric HCl to form salt and water; rapid onset (minutes), short duration (30-60 min), good only for occasional dyspepsia and heartburn, weak in erosive esophagitis or true ulcer disease. The adverse effects fall out of the cation: aluminum → constipation (plus hypophosphatemia), magnesium → diarrhea, so the two are combined to counterbalance the bowel. Calcium carbonate is the preferred antacid in pregnancy; sodium bicarbonate is a systemic alkalinizer used for metabolic acidosis and salicylate toxicity but risks sodium overload; bismuth subsalicylate joins H. pylori therapy and famously turns the tongue and stool grayish-black. Parmar repeats one OTC-safety line all lecture: don't use an antacid beyond 2 weeks without seeing a doctor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Aluminum → constipation; magnesium → diarrhea — combined to counterbalance."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CaCO₃ = preferred antacid in pregnancy; NaHCO₃ = systemic alkalinizer (acidosis, salicylate toxicity)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "H2RAs — REVERSIBLE, ~60-70%. Ranitidine, famotidine, cimetidine competitively and reversibly block H2 receptors, cutting acid ~60-70% and working best against nocturnal (rather than meal-stimulated) secretion — hence dosing at bedtime, and the mnemonic that the ‘-tidine’ drugs are taken before you dine. Two H2RA-specific facts earn flags: tachyphylaxis develops within days to weeks of continuous use, and reversible confusion can appear in the elderly or renally impaired. Ranitidine (Zantac) is the one Parmar brings back specifically to tell its story: it was pulled from the market because the manufacturing process generated the carcinogen NDMA — “that's why now it's part of my lecture,” reformulated and returned."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "H2RAs reversibly block H2 → ~60-70% acid reduction, best nocturnally; tachyphylaxis in days-weeks."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CIMETIDINE IS THE OUTLIER. Among the H2RAs, cimetidine is the first-generation drug that carries the baggage: antiandrogenic effects at high dose (gynecomastia, galactorrhea), a rise in serum creatinine without true renal injury, and a thick list of CYP-mediated interactions (LO 35.4). Famotidine is the one to default to — about 20× more potent than cimetidine, longer-acting (~12 h vs ~6 h), and largely free of those effects. Parmar called the famotidine-over-cimetidine point out as something you will actually use prescribing."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PPIs — IRREVERSIBLE, >90%. The ‘-prazole’ drugs (omeprazole, esomeprazole, pantoprazole, lansoprazole, dexlansoprazole, rabeprazole) are prodrugs that, once activated in the acidic parietal-cell canaliculi, irreversibly inhibit the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase and suppress >90% of basal and stimulated acid. Because the bond is covalent, the effect outlasts the drug: plasma half-life is short, but secretion only recovers as new pumps are made over ~18-24 hours. Dose before a meal for best effect. Two PK pearls Parmar repeated: esomeprazole and pantoprazole are the only IV PPIs, and long-term use carries real risks (next LO covers B12; also hypomagnesemia, fracture from impaired calcium absorption, and C. difficile from lost acid barrier). Use the lowest effective dose for the shortest duration."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PPIs = prodrugs that irreversibly inhibit the pump → >90% suppression; recovery needs ~18-24 h of new pump synthesis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Only IV-available PPIs: esomeprazole and pantoprazole."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PCAB, MISOPROSTOL, SUCRALFATE — THE REST OF THE LADDER. Vonoprazan, a potassium-competitive acid blocker (PCAB), reversibly competes with K⁺ at the pump, is acid-stable with rapid onset, and does not need acid activation — a newer agent Parmar notes “wasn't in last year's lecture.” Misoprostol is a synthetic PGE1 analog that inhibits acid and boosts the mucous barrier; its niche is NSAID-induced ulcer prophylaxis, and it is contraindicated in pregnancy (abortifacient). Sucralfate is a sucrose-sulfate / aluminum-hydroxide complex that forms a viscous protective gel over the ulcer base — but only in an acidic pH, which sets up its key interaction rule (LO 35.4)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Vonoprazan (PCAB) = reversible K-competitive pump blocker; no acid activation needed."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Misoprostol = PGE1 analog for NSAID-ulcer prophylaxis; pregnancy-contraindicated."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "PPI vs PCAB: both target the pump, but PPIs bind irreversibly and need acid activation, while vonoprazan blocks the K⁺ site reversibly and is acid-stable."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Read the suffix: -tidine = H2RA, -prazole = PPI, -prazan = PCAB. The endings sort the class faster than any list."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Don't pin gynecomastia on ‘the H2 blocker’ generically — it is cimetidine specifically; famotidine and ranitidine are free of the antiandrogenic effect."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Walk the acid-suppression ladder from weakest to strongest and name the one signature adverse effect that flags each rung."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Compare the relationship of histamine-2 receptor antagonists to proton pump inhibitors and the effect of acid suppression on vitamin B12 and intrinsic factor", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The whole point of this LO is one comparison: H2RA versus PPI. Parmar drew the contrast explicitly in numbers, and the exam loves it because the two drugs sit on the same pathway but act at different points — a receptor versus the pump."}, {"t": "p", "x": "POTENCY AND DURABILITY. An H2RA reversibly blocks a single receptor (H2), so it removes only the histamine input and reaches about 60-70% acid reduction — strongest against nocturnal acid, and blunted further by tachyphylaxis over days to weeks. A PPI shuts the final common step, the pump itself, and does so irreversibly, reaching >90% suppression of both basal and stimulated acid with an effect that outlasts the drug. So the relationship is simple and directional: same axis, but the PPI is more potent, more durable, and not subject to tolerance. That is why the typical sequence is a PPI to heal, then an H2RA for maintenance once erosions are gone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PPI >90% irreversible vs H2RA ~60-70% reversible (nocturnal, tachyphylaxis) — PPI is more potent and durable."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE B12 COST OF ACID SUPPRESSION. Strength has a price over time. Both classes — PPIs on slide 17, long-term H2RAs on slide 11 — decrease the bioavailability of vitamin B12. The mechanism is the whole reason this LO pairs acid with B12: gastric acid is required to cleave cobalamin (B12) off dietary protein before it can be picked up for absorption. Suppress acid for long enough (the H2RA warning specifies ≥2 years) and that release step fails, so serum B12 drifts down — a quiet, chronic-use adverse effect rather than an acute one."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronic acid suppression (PPI or long-term H2RA) ↓vitamin B12 — acid is needed to free B12 from food."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INTRINSIC FACTOR — ADDED SCAFFOLDING. Parmar didn't cover intrinsic factor, but the LO names it, so for completeness: intrinsic factor is made by the same parietal cells that secrete acid and is the carrier that B12 needs for absorption in the terminal ileum — which is why loss of parietal-cell function (as in atrophic gastritis or autoimmune pernicious anemia) causes B12 deficiency. Standard acid-suppressive drugs lower B12 by blocking acid-dependent release of B12 from food, not by destroying intrinsic factor."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "H2RA vs PPI: same pathway, different target — H2RA blocks the H2 receptor (~60-70%, reversible, tachyphylaxis); PPI blocks the pump (>90%, irreversible)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Picture the sequence: PPI to heal the erosive disease, then step down to an H2RA for maintenance once erosions have resolved."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Don't confuse the two B12 mechanisms: acid-suppressive drugs impair acid-dependent release of B12 from food; they do not knock out intrinsic factor (that is the pernicious-anemia route)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two patients need GERD control — one started on an H2RA, one on a PPI. What two features make the PPI the stronger choice, and what is the long-term cost of that strength?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the clinically significant drug interactions of acid-suppressive and mucosal-protective agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar flagged the interaction material directly — “focus from exam point of view, this is important” — while warning that the full list reads as an unmemorizable laundry. The way through is to sort by mechanism: enzyme inhibition (CYP), a change in gastric pH, and physical binding/chelation. Get the three buckets and any specific pair is predictable."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CIMETIDINE = CYP450 INHIBITION. Cimetidine is the broad CYP450 inhibitor of the group: it raises levels of warfarin, diazepam, and eletriptan (and many others) by slowing their metabolism, which is why those co-prescriptions get dangerous. It also raises serum creatinine without causing real renal impairment (it blocks creatinine's tubular secretion, not filtration). Famotidine has far fewer interactions — the practical reason it has displaced cimetidine. Slide 14 lays the serious interactions out as warfarin / diazepam / eletriptan; pin those three as your representatives."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cimetidine = CYP450 inhibitor → ↑warfarin / diazepam / eletriptan; also ↑SCr without renal injury."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PPI + CLOPIDOGREL = THE CYP2C19 TRAP. This is the single highest-yield PPI interaction. Clopidogrel is a prodrug that must be activated by CYP2C19; omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19, so they reduce clopidogrel's activation and blunt its antiplatelet effect — avoid the combination, and reach for pantoprazole (minimal CYP2C19 effect) when a stented patient needs a PPI. Separately, because PPIs raise gastric pH, they impair absorption of drugs that need an acidic environment (digoxin, ketoconazole, itraconazole) — the pH-change bucket."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Omeprazole/esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19 → ↓activation of clopidogrel; use pantoprazole instead."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE pH AND BINDING RULES. Two more patterns close the LO. Sucralfate needs an acidic pH to form its gel, so it must not be co-administered with PPIs, H2RAs, or antacids, and it impairs absorption of quinolone antibiotics by binding them — the chelation/binding bucket. Antacids likewise bind or chelate many drugs (tetracyclines, bisphosphonates, iron, digoxin, quinolones), so the fix is mechanical: separate dosing by ~2-4 hours rather than co-administer."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sucralfate needs acidic pH (no PPI/H2RA/antacid co-admin) and impairs quinolone absorption."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Antacids chelate tetracyclines/bisphosphonates/iron/quinolones → space dosing ~2-4 h."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Stent on clopidogrel and needs acid suppression? Choose pantoprazole — avoid omeprazole and esomeprazole (CYP2C19 inhibitors that blunt clopidogrel)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cimetidine raising creatinine is a pseudo-rise — it blocks tubular secretion of creatinine, so the GFR is actually unchanged."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Co-dosing sucralfate with a PPI — the raised pH stops sucralfate from gelling, so the protectant simply doesn't work. Space them, or pick one."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Three different mechanisms drive the interactions in this lecture — CYP inhibition, a raised gastric pH, and physical binding. Give the headline drug pair for each."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe the regimens used for Helicobacter pylori eradication", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar time-boxed this to a few minutes but framed it as high-stakes — H. pylori is a common infection linked to peptic ulcer disease and an established risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma and MALT lymphoma. The cancer link is the reason eradication is taken seriously, and the reason the rules tightened in the 2024 guidelines."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY IT'S COMBINATION THERAPY. Eradication always pairs acid suppression with antibiotics, and each half has a job. The PPI (or PCAB) suppresses acid and promotes mucosal healing — and a higher gastric pH also makes the antibiotics work better. The antibiotics kill the organism and cut recurrence and complications. Bismuth subsalicylate adds antimicrobial punch and helps overcome antibiotic resistance. Antibiotic selection is driven by resistance patterns, prior use, allergy, and cost — which is exactly why clarithromycin fell out of favor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "H. pylori = risk factor for peptic ulcer disease, gastric adenocarcinoma, and MALT lymphoma."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE GOLD-STANDARD REGIMEN. The preferred first-line is the 14-day Optimized Bismuth Quadruple Therapy (BQT): PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth. (Parmar: don't sweat the dosing frequency — just know it as the gold standard.) The modern 14-day alternatives are PCAB Dual Therapy (vonoprazan + amoxicillin) and Rifabutin-Based Triple Therapy. The key change to know: clarithromycin was dropped from first-line use because of widespread resistance in North America, which made the old clarithromycin-triple unreliable. Commonly used antibiotics now are tetracycline, metronidazole, amoxicillin, and rifabutin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "First-line: 14-day BQT = PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth; alternatives = PCAB-dual, rifabutin-triple."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Clarithromycin dropped from first-line → resistance."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CONFIRMATION IS NOW MANDATORY. The 2024-guideline headline Parmar stressed: after the 14-day course, proof of eradication is now mandatory for every treated patient — documented with a fecal antigen test, urea breath test, or gastric biopsy. Eradicating the organism measurably reduces the risk of PUD complications (bleeding, perforation, gastric-outlet obstruction) and of gastric cancer, so confirming the cure is the point, not an afterthought."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Eradication confirmation is mandatory (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) after therapy."}, {"t": "key", "x": "First-line H. pylori = 14-day BQT (PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth); PCAB-dual and rifabutin-triple are the modern alternatives."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reaching for clarithromycin triple — it was dropped from first-line for resistance. And acid suppression alone never eradicates the organism."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "After treating, confirm eradication with a fecal antigen test, urea breath test, or biopsy — it is now mandatory for every patient."}, {"t": "q", "x": "An H. pylori-positive ulcer patient in a high-clarithromycin-resistance region: what is the gold-standard regimen, what changed about it recently, and what must you do after 14 days?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "List the categories of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar builds this whole lecture as a receptor map, so the first move is to learn the categories, not the individual drugs. Nausea and vomiting are integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema and the vomiting center, and four neurotransmitter-receptor pairs feed them: ACh (M1), histamine (H1), substance P (NK1), and serotonin (5-HT3). Each pair has a drug class that blocks it. Two adjunct families — cannabinoids (CB1 agonists) and benzodiazepines (GABA-A modulators) — plus dexamethasone and olanzapine round out the rescue/adjuvant tier."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DRUG-ENDING SHORTCUTS. Two name endings do most of the binning for you: the -setrons (ondansetron, dolasetron, granisetron, palonosetron) are the 5-HT3 antagonists, and the -pitants (aprepitant, fosaprepitant, netupitant, rolapitant) are the NK1 antagonists. The D2 antagonists are a mixed-name group (prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, amisulpride), and the antihistamine/antimuscarinic motion-sickness agents are scopolamine (M1) and meclizine/dimenhydrinate (H1). Prokinetics are a separate list organized by mechanism, and metoclopramide deliberately appears in both buckets."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "-setron = 5-HT3 antagonist; -pitant = NK1 antagonist."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Four vomiting receptors: M1, H1, NK1, 5-HT3 — one drug class each."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Antiemetics sort by receptor target: M1 (scopolamine), H1 (meclizine/dimenhydrinate), D2 (the mixed group), 5-HT3 (-setrons), NK1 (-pitants), plus cannabinoid/benzo/steroid adjuncts."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The -setron / -pitant endings bin two whole classes on sight — anchor the rest of the lecture on these two name tells."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Scopolamine = M1 (muscarinic); meclizine/dimenhydrinate = H1 (histamine). Same motion-sickness use, different receptors."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Parmar groups antiemetics by their receptor target. Name the four core receptors and the drug class that blocks each."}]}, {"id": 7, "statement": "Discuss the mechanism of action of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism story is the heart of the lecture, and Parmar tells it as one vomiting-reflex framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema and the vomiting center in the floor of the fourth ventricle, and each antiemetic class simply blocks one input. Get the framework first and every drug's MOA is just \"which receptor does it sit on.\""}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TWO CHEMO PATHWAYS — ACUTE vs DELAYED. Chemotherapy drives nausea two ways, and this is the most-repeated point in the lecture. Peripherally, it makes enterochromaffin cells release serotonin onto 5-HT3 receptors on vagal afferents — the acute phase (resolves within ~24 h). Centrally, it triggers release of substance P onto NK1 receptors in the area postrema — the delayed phase (days 1-5). So 5-HT3 antagonists (setrons) own the acute phase and NK1 antagonists (-pitants) own the delayed phase; a highly emetogenic regimen needs both, plus dexamethasone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute CINV = serotonin → 5-HT3 (peripheral); delayed CINV = substance P → NK1 (central)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Setrons cover the acute phase; -pitants cover the delayed phase."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE OTHER BLOCKERS, BY SITE. Scopolamine (M1) and the H1 antihistamines act centrally at the area postrema and on the vestibular system — which is why they treat motion sickness but, as Parmar stresses, are ineffective at the CTZ (so they don't cover CINV). D2 antagonists block dopamine in the CTZ. Setrons work at two sites at once — centrally in the area postrema and peripherally on GI vagal terminals — and selectively, without meaningful D2, H1, or muscarinic activity. NK1 antagonists block substance P in the area postrema and on vagal afferents."}, {"t": "p", "x": "METOCLOPRAMIDE — THE DUAL DRUG. Metoclopramide is the one to understand mechanistically, because it works in two compartments. Centrally it is a D2 antagonist at the CTZ (the antiemetic effect, no antipsychotic activity). Peripherally it facilitates cholinergic transmission in the gut — relieving dopamine's brake on ACh release — which raises lower-esophageal-sphincter tone, accelerates gastric emptying, and promotes small-bowel transit (the prokinetic effect, revisited in LO 36.3). That second action is why it treats diabetic gastroparesis, and why the GLP-1 weight-loss agents — which slow gastric emptying — can produce the gastroparesis metoclopramide reverses."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PROKINETICS BY MECHANISM. The prokinetic class is a mechanism quiz waiting to happen: erythromycin is a motilin receptor agonist (short-term only — receptors downregulate); prucalopride is a selective 5-HT4 agonist; bethanechol is a direct muscarinic agonist; and neostigmine is an AChE inhibitor (raising gut ACh, used for colonic pseudo-obstruction). All converge on the same outcome — coordinated GI motility and faster gastric emptying — by different receptors."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Erythromycin = motilin agonist; prucalopride = 5-HT4 agonist; neostigmine = AChE inhibitor."}, {"t": "key", "x": "One framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema → vomiting center, and each antiemetic class blocks one receptor input (M1/H1/D2/5-HT3/NK1)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Acute CINV = 5-HT3/serotonin (peripheral, <24 h); delayed CINV = NK1/substance P (central, days 1-5). Phase tells you the class."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Metoclopramide is two drugs in one: central D2 antagonist (antiemetic) + peripheral cholinergic facilitation (prokinetic — ↑LES tone, gastric emptying)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A chemotherapy patient is nauseated immediately, then again on day 3. Which mediator and receptor drive each episode, and which drug covers each?"}]}, {"id": 8, "statement": "Discuss the therapeutic and adverse effects of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Therapeutic uses cluster around a short vocabulary you'll see repeated on every slide — CINV (chemotherapy-induced), PONV (postoperative), RINV (radiation-induced), motion sickness, and gastroparesis. Because the indications overlap so heavily, the exam discriminates by adverse effect: each class has a signature toxicity, and that's where Parmar spends his emphasis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "D2 ANTAGONISTS → EPS, AND TWO DISTINCT BOXED WARNINGS. Because they block dopamine, all D2 antagonists cause extrapyramidal symptoms — dystonia, akathisia, parkinsonism, and tardive dyskinesia. The high-yield split is the boxed warnings. Metoclopramide carries a boxed warning for tardive dyskinesia that can be irreversible; risk climbs with duration and cumulative dose, so avoid use beyond 12 weeks — a point that matters because its prokinetic role tempts longer courses. Droperidol instead carries a boxed warning for QT prolongation and torsades: all patients need a 12-lead ECG before dosing and monitoring 2-3 hours after, and it's limited to PONV. Parmar walks through the droperidol ECG requirement specifically to show \"how careful you need to be\" with this agent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Metoclopramide boxed warning = irreversible tardive dyskinesia; limit to ≤12 weeks."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Droperidol boxed warning = QT/torsades; 12-lead ECG before and after."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE QT CLUSTER AND THE APOMORPHINE TRAP. QT prolongation recurs across antiemetics — droperidol, amisulpride, the setrons, and the macrolide prokinetics — so combining them stacks the risk. Among setrons, palonosetron (2nd-generation: high affinity, long half-life, covers acute AND delayed CINV) has the least QT effect, while ondansetron is the one agent that requires dose adjustment in hepatic insufficiency. The setron toxicity worth memorizing is the hard contraindication: ondansetron + apomorphine → profound hypotension and loss of consciousness. Other classes have milder signatures — H1/M1 agents cause sedation, dry mouth, blurred vision; cannabinoids cause euphoria/dysphoria and, chronically, cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome; dexamethasone brings hyperglycemia, weight gain, and infection risk."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ADJUVANTS AND THE GUIDELINE COMBINATION. Three rescue/adjuvant agents earn their own niches: benzodiazepines (lorazepam, alprazolam) treat anticipatory nausea where anxiety is the trigger; olanzapine — a multi-receptor (D2/5-HT2,3/H1/M) blocker — is a key component of four-drug prophylaxis for highly emetogenic chemotherapy (HEC); and dexamethasone is the steroid backbone of multi-drug regimens. The guideline combination to hold onto: 5-HT3 antagonist + NK1 antagonist + dexamethasone, with olanzapine added as the fourth drug for HEC."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ondansetron + apomorphine → profound hypotension; hard contraindication."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HEC four-drug regimen: 5-HT3 + NK1 + dexamethasone + olanzapine."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Two D2 antagonists, two different boxed warnings: metoclopramide → irreversible TD (≤12 wk), droperidol → QT/torsades (ECG). Don't swap them."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Palonosetron is the setron with the least QT effect and the only one covering both acute and delayed CINV — the long half-life does both jobs."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "For HEC, give the four-drug regimen: 5-HT3 + NK1 + dexamethasone + olanzapine. For anticipatory nausea, reach for a benzodiazepine."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two D2 antagonists both cause EPS — but each carries a different boxed warning. Contrast metoclopramide's and droperidol's boxed warnings and the monitoring each demands."}]}, {"id": 9, "statement": "Discuss the potential contraindications and drug interactions of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Two interaction themes carry this LO, and Parmar flags both as testable: the Parkinson's contraindication that follows every dopamine blocker, and the CYP-P450 interactions of the NK1 antagonists — which he ties directly to COMLEX drug-interaction questions after talking to a student who took the exam."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PARKINSON'S — THE D2 CONTRAINDICATION. Parkinson's disease is dopamine-neuron loss, so a drug that blocks dopamine worsens it. That makes every D2 antagonist antiemetic contraindicated in Parkinson's — prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, and amisulpride alike. It's the same mechanism that gives the class its EPS, so the contraindication and the adverse-effect profile are one idea, not two."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "All D2 antagonists are contraindicated in Parkinson's disease (dopamine blockade)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NK1 / CYP3A4 / DEXAMETHASONE INTERACTION. This is the cluster Parmar spends the most interaction-time on. Aprepitant, fosaprepitant, and netupitant are moderate CYP3A4 inhibitors. Dexamethasone — the steroid in the standard regimen — is a CYP3A4 substrate, so co-administering these NK1 agents raises dexamethasone levels and risks toxicity: the fix is to reduce the dexamethasone dose. The deliberate contrast is rolapitant, which inhibits CYP2D6, NOT CYP3A4 — so it does not touch dexamethasone metabolism and needs no dose adjustment (making it the choice for patients already on many CYP3A4 drugs). The exam version is a statement-evaluation: \"this NK1 drug is a moderate CYP3A4 inhibitor, so you do/don't adjust dexamethasone\" — and rolapitant is the trap."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Aprepitant/fosaprepitant/netupitant inhibit CYP3A4 → reduce dexamethasone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rolapitant = CYP2D6, not CYP3A4 → no dexamethasone adjustment."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SMALLER INTERACTION FLAGS. Round out the LO with the discrete contraindications: ondansetron + apomorphine (profound hypotension — never combine), the additive QT risk when QT-prolongers are stacked (droperidol/amisulpride/setrons/macrolides), and amisulpride/droperidol contraindicated with a prolonged baseline QT. Among prokinetics, the macrolides (erythromycin) also prolong QT, and the cannabinoids carry the chronic-use cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome caveat."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Rolapitant is CYP2D6, NOT CYP3A4 — so it needs no dexamethasone adjustment. Aprepitant/fosaprepitant/netupitant (CYP3A4) DO. This is the planted COMLEX distractor."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Any D2 antagonist + Parkinson's = stop. Pick a non-dopaminergic antiemetic (setron, NK1 antagonist, or an H1 agent) instead."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Inhibiting CYP3A4 raises the substrate (dexamethasone), so you reduce its dose — not increase it. Inhibitor → higher levels → lower the dose."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two NK1 antagonists are given alongside dexamethasone. Why does aprepitant force a dexamethasone dose change while rolapitant does not?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. ‘The H2 blocker causes gynecomastia.’ Only cimetidine is antiandrogenic (gynecomastia/galactorrhea) and a broad CYP450 inhibitor; famotidine and ranitidine are largely free of both — don't generalize cimetidine's baggage to the class. → LO 35.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. PPI of choice with clopidogrel. Omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19 and blunt clopidogrel activation; the safe pick is pantoprazole, not ‘any PPI is fine.’ → LO 35.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Co-dosing sucralfate with a PPI/antacid. Sucralfate needs an acidic pH to gel; raising pH with an acid suppressor makes it inert. Space them or choose one. → LO 35.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Clarithromycin-triple as first-line H. pylori therapy. Clarithromycin was dropped for resistance; first-line is 14-day BQT, and eradication confirmation is mandatory. → LO 35.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Meclizine is an H2 antagonist. Meclizine and dimenhydrinate are H1 antihistamines for motion sickness; the -tidine H2 blockers are for acid suppression. Parmar plants this exact distractor — \"be very careful. No.\" → LO 36.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Acute = NK1, delayed = 5-HT3. It's the reverse: the acute phase is serotonin/5-HT3 (setrons), the delayed phase is substance P/NK1 (-pitants). Phase tells you the class. → LO 36.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Same boxed warning for both D2 antagonists. They differ — metoclopramide = irreversible tardive dyskinesia (≤12 wk), droperidol = QT/torsades (mandatory ECG). Don't merge them. → LO 36.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Every NK1 antagonist needs a dexamethasone dose cut. Only the CYP3A4 inhibitors (aprepitant/fosaprepitant/netupitant) do. Rolapitant is CYP2D6 → no adjustment. → LO 36.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. “older man on an H2 blocker develops breast tenderness” → think cimetidine (antiandrogenic) — switch to famotidine."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. “post-stent patient on clopidogrel started on omeprazole” → flag the CYP2C19 interaction — change to pantoprazole."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. “sucralfate plus a PPI, ulcer not healing” → the raised pH inactivated the sucralfate — separate the doses."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. “H. pylori-positive ulcer, high local clarithromycin resistance” → 14-day bismuth quadruple therapy, then confirm eradication."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"motion-sickness drug is an H2 antagonist\" → false — it's H1 (meclizine/dimenhydrinate); H2 blockers are the -tidines for acid."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"nausea on day 3 after chemo\" → delayed phase = substance P/NK1 → add a -pitant, not another setron."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"12-lead ECG required before and after the antiemetic\" → droperidol (QT boxed warning), not the TD warning of metoclopramide."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"NK1 agent that needs NO dexamethasone change\" → rolapitant (CYP2D6, not CYP3A4)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Acid-secretion physiology & the parietal-cell pump feed the antiemetic/prokinetic receptor logic — also Lec 36 (Antiemetic & Prokinetic Agents), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — H. pylori, NSAID ulcers, and the ulcer/upper-GI-bleed thread — callback to Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Misoprostol (PGE1) and the prostaglandin/NSAID-ulcer axis — revisited in later GI & pharmacology coverage"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Metoclopramide's dual antiemetic/prokinetic role + GLP-1-induced gastroparesis — also Lec 35 (Drugs for Peptic Ulcers & Gastric Acidity), this block"}]}]}, "37": {"prof": "Dr. Norman Rose", "tldr": "Hemodynamic stability decides the path — unstable or peritonitic goes straight to the OR; stable goes to FAST/CT and observation — and organ-injury grading drives the rest. The spleen dominates.", "mustKnows": ["1. Kehr's sign is your board question. Kehr's sign is left-shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation by blood pooling under the diaphragm — classically from a splenic injury. Rose called it out by name as your board question; it occurs in about half of cases, and the hiccups that accompany it are the same phrenic-nerve irritation.", "2. Stability decides the path. Run the ABCs first. An unstable or peritonitic patient (hypotension, tachycardia, distended/tight abdomen, positive FAST) goes straight to the OR for laparotomy. A patient you can stabilize with 1–2 L crystalloid earns time for a CT and a trial of observation.", "3. Grade the spleen I–V. Splenic injury is graded I–V: I–III (capsular tear → through-and-through laceration) are usually repairable or observable; IV–V (stellate/crush, bisection, hilar injury, shattered spleen) are not repairable and need splenectomy. Delayed rupture can present up to ~2 weeks later.", "4. Splenectomy risks OPSI — save the spleen in kids. After splenectomy the patient loses filtering of encapsulated bacteria and makes less IgM and opsonins → overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI), worst in children. That is why we repair or observe (Types I–III) rather than remove whenever it is safe.", "5. Renal hematuria localizes the injury. 70–80% of renal injuries are blunt (MVA, falls). Hematuria means the injury reached the collecting system / renal pelvis, and the depth of the laceration determines whether surgery is needed. The trap: a child's UPJ avulsion can give a NEGATIVE urinalysis (no urine reaches the bladder).", "6. Cullen vs Gray-Turner. Two bruising signs of intra-abdominal/retroperitoneal bleeding: Cullen sign = periumbilical ecchymosis; Gray-Turner sign = flank ecchymosis. Bruising not explained by the surface injury should make you suspicious of bleeding underneath."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe abdominal anatomy and mapping", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Rose opens the way an old-school trauma surgeon does: before he lays a hand on the patient he pictures what's going on inside — skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum stripped away, the organs laid bare. The whole lecture rests on this. For trauma the single most useful map is the four quadrants, because the quadrant plus the mechanism tells you which organs are at risk. (The finer nine-region map — epigastric, umbilical, hypogastric, and the paired hypochondriac, lumbar, and iliac regions — is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma.)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "RETROPERITONEAL VS INTRAPERITONEAL — THE KEY SPLIT. The dividing question for every organ is whether it is fixed (retroperitoneal) or mobile (intraperitoneal). Fixed organs cannot dodge a force, so they take crush injuries against the spine: the pancreas (Rose's biggest worry — it can be crushed or even bifurcated against the vertebral column), the kidneys and adrenals, the duodenum, and the ascending/descending colon. Mobile organs slip out of the way — the small intestine usually escapes blunt force, and the stomach or colon get into trouble mainly when markedly distended. The sigmoid is fixed enough that a LLQ stab wound reliably catches it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Retroperitoneal/fixed organs (pancreas, kidneys, duodenum) take crush-against-spine injury; mobile organs slip away."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "LUQ holds the spleen; RUQ the liver; a LLQ stab catches the fixed sigmoid colon."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE VASCULATURE YOU MUST KNOW. The abdominal aorta is the largest artery in the body; it starts below the diaphragm and bifurcates into the common iliacs at about L4–L5. That landmark is not trivia — it is why a REBOA balloon can occlude the aorta in one zone but not across the renal arteries (LO 37.5). A crushing or penetrating injury to the great vessels is the bleed that kills fastest."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Abdominal aorta bifurcates into common iliacs at ~L4–L5 (largest artery in the body)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "For trauma, think in four quadrants: quadrant + mechanism = the organs at risk. The nine-region map is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Retroperitoneal/fixed (pancreas, kidney, duodenum, ascending/descending colon) get crushed against the spine; intraperitoneal/mobile (small bowel) dodge the blow."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The spleen (LUQ) and liver (RUQ) both have thin capsules that tear easily — which is exactly why they top the solid-organ injury list."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rose says he mentally strips away the skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum before he touches a trauma patient. What is the diagnostic payoff of picturing the organs by quadrant?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe diagnostic imaging and lab studies requested for abdominal trauma patients", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. If Rose makes one point in this lecture, it is ultrasound: that's the thing that's going to make all the difference. The bedside FAST exam (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) is fast, cheap, repeatable, and increasingly done on a phone probe — he told the class to chase the ultrasound teams in the ED and learn it. FAST hunts for free fluid (blood), air, and gross organ injury in the liver, kidneys, and spleen, and the density of the fluid even distinguishes blood from serous fluid. The volume of blood in the abdomen can be estimated from it."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE STABILITY-DRIVEN PATHWAY — THE SPINE OF THE LECTURE. Do the ABCs first and ask one question: is the patient stable? The unstable patient — hypotensive, tachycardic, a tense and distended abdomen, dull to percussion, positive FAST — is bleeding too fast to image. You resuscitate and go straight to the OR for an open exploration; there is no time to laparoscope and no time to scan. The patient you can stabilize with a couple of liters of crystalloid (mild hypotension that responds) has bought time — now you can get a CT, a focused ultrasound, and decide between operation and observation. Stability, not the organ, drives the disposition."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Trauma disposition: unstable/peritonitic → OR (open); stabilizes → CT and observe."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN ULTRASOUND ISN'T ENOUGH — CT, CONTRAST, AND THE OLD PLAIN FILM. In a non-critical patient, CT is the best quick screen (MRI takes too long); the one place you reach for contrast is the urinary tract, to look for extravasation of urine and gauge the renal injury. Before ultrasound, all Rose had was an upright chest/abdomen film hunting for free air under the diaphragm and signs of peritoneal irritation — worth knowing as the fallback when imaging is thin. And through all of it: nothing beats a good history of how the trauma happened."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE LABS, READ FOR WHAT THEY MEAN. The H/H (hemoglobin/hematocrit) lags reality but tells you how much blood was lost and how many units you may need — it runs a step behind the bleed, so trend it. On the differential, watch the white count: a left shift with rising leukocytes means the body is mobilizing white cells against contamination (think a perforated viscus). The UA looks for blood; amylase/lipase flag the pancreas; liver and renal panels, electrolytes, and an EKG round out the metabolic picture. Read the H/H for blood loss and the WBC for contamination — they answer different questions."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "H/H tracks blood loss (and lags); a WBC left shift flags contamination/perforation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Reach for contrast in trauma mainly for the urinary tract (urine extravasation = renal injury)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Workup order: ABCs → is the patient stable? Unstable + positive FAST → straight to the OR. Stabilizes → CT, then observe vs operate."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "FAST finds free fluid, air, and organ injury at the bedside — Rose's single biggest message was to learn ultrasound. Density tells blood from serous fluid."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "The H/H answers 'how much blood was lost' (and lags); the WBC left shift answers 'is there contamination' — two different labs for two different questions."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two blunt-trauma patients both have a positive FAST. One is hypotensive with a tense abdomen; the other stabilizes after 1.5 L of crystalloid. Why do they go to two completely different places?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "List different types of abdominal trauma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism tells you what to look for, so name it. Blunt / compression (the common one) drives organs against the spine and breaks ribs over the spleen and liver. Penetrating (stab, gunshot) injures along its trajectory — and the trajectory, not just the entry point, is what matters: a wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because the diaphragm rides up to the nipples on expiration. Crush is severe compression (steering wheel, a wall). Iatrogenic injury is caused by us during an operation. Blast injury drives foreign bodies inward and combines penetrating with crush."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PENETRATING: TRACE THE PATH. With a penetrating wound you reason from the direction of penetration and the instrument used — was it from the flank, transthoracic, anterior, or posterior? Rose's nail-gun case drove this home: the nail tracked far enough lateral and retroperitoneal that it spared the kidney, ureter, and vasculature — a quick UA confirmed the kidney was fine, and he removed the nail with an OR ready in case the patient crashed. The lesson is that the path predicts the organs, and many penetrating injuries still warrant exploration."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen (diaphragm rises on expiration)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Iatrogenic splenic injury = capsule torn during a LUQ operation (traction on the gastrosplenic ligament)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "For penetrating trauma, the trajectory predicts the injured organs — a sub-nipple wound can breach the diaphragm because it rides up on expiration."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Always reconstruct the mechanism first (blunt vs penetrating vs crush vs iatrogenic vs blast) — it sets which organs you hunt for and whether to explore."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Treating the entry point as the injury. The path is the injury; a flank or transthoracic angle changes everything about what's hit."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rose says that for a penetrating wound you have to 'figure out the direction.' Why does the trajectory matter more than the entry point?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe splenic, liver, and renal injuries", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the heart of the lecture, and the spleen is its center. The spleen is the most frequently injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma and the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its capsule is paper-thin and its attachments (gastrosplenic ligament, attachments to the diaphragm) tear easily. Injury comes from penetrating, blunt, or iatrogenic mechanisms — and isolated splenic injury occurs in only about 30% of cases, so when you find a hurt spleen, look for the stomach, left kidney, pancreas, and ribs too."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GRADE THE SPLEEN I–V. Your radiologist reports a type, not a dissertation, so you must know what each means. Type I = minor capsular tear/laceration (easily repaired). Type II = capsular avulsion, most of the spleen intact. Type III = major parenchymal fracture or a through-and-through laceration (stab/gunshot) — still usually repairable with technique. Types IV–V are different animals: severe stellate fracture, crush or bisection, hilar injury, and the shattered spleen — not repairable, so they come out. The clean cutoff: I–III repair or observe; IV–V splenectomy."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Spleen grades I–III are often repairable/observable; IV–V (crush/bisection/shattered) need splenectomy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SPLENIC SIGNS — AND THE BOARD QUESTION. Once blood is in the abdomen it irritates the diaphragm, and the prof flagged the consequence as your board question: Kehr's sign — left-shoulder pain referred from diaphragmatic irritation, occurring in about half of splenic injuries, often with hiccups (same phrenic-nerve irritation). Ballance's sign (fixed dullness to percussion ± a palpable mass) is described but Rose said he never saw it. And learn the two bruising signs: Cullen sign = periumbilical ecchymosis, Gray-Turner sign = flank ecchymosis — bruising not explained by the surface injury should make you suspicious of bleeding underneath."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Kehr's sign = left-shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation by splenic blood — the prof's explicit board flag."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cullen = periumbilical ecchymosis; Gray-Turner = flank ecchymosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "SAVE THE SPLEEN — OPSI AND DELAYED RUPTURE. Why bend over backward to repair or observe? Because the asplenic patient loses the filter for encapsulated bacteria and makes less IgM and opsonins → overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI), worst in children — so in kids especially we save the spleen, and nonoperative management is done only in an ICU with an OR immediately available (Rose insisted a county hospital transfer its stable splenic-injury child to him for exactly that reason). Watch too for delayed splenic rupture: a subcapsular hematoma that looks to be resolving can rupture ~2 weeks later and bring the patient back in shock."}, {"t": "p", "x": "LIVER — SAME THIN CAPSULE, GRADED I–VI. The liver tells the same story: thin capsule, easy laceration, graded by hematoma size and laceration depth. I subcapsular hematoma <10% / laceration <1 cm; II hematoma 10–50% / laceration 1–3 cm deep; III >50% or expanding / laceration >3 cm deep; IV 25–75% of a lobe (1–3 Couinaud segments); V >75% or >3 segments, including juxtahepatic venous (retrohepatic IVC / major hepatic veins); VI hepatic avulsion. The surgeon must know the segmental blood supply because you can resect part of the liver and survive on the rest — even on just the right side."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Liver is graded by hematoma size + laceration depth (I–VI); juxtahepatic venous injury (grade V) is the dangerous one."}, {"t": "p", "x": "RENAL — BLUNT, BLEEDS, AND THE HEMATURIA RULE. 70–80% of renal injuries are blunt (MVA, falls, deceleration onto the flank/back), and the kidney sits in the retroperitoneum, so injury makes a retroperitoneal hematoma — suspect it in a shocked patient with rib / vertebral / transverse-process fractures. The key clinical logic: hematuria means the injury reached the collecting system / renal pelvis. Grade by depth — I contusion/subcapsular hematoma; II cortical laceration <1 cm; III deeper laceration not reaching the collecting system; IV through the corticomedullary junction INTO the collecting system (urine extravasation) or a segmental vessel; V main-vessel thrombosis/avulsion or a shattered kidney. It is the depth of the laceration that determines whether surgery is needed; an unstable patient goes to the OR regardless, where a one-shot IVP may be the only imaging you get."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Hematuria → injury reached the renal pelvis/collecting system; depth of laceration determines surgery."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Child + rapid deceleration + negative UA → suspect UPJ avulsion (no urine reaches the bladder)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Kehr's sign (left-shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation) is the prof's explicit board flag for splenic injury — paired with hiccups from the same phrenic irritation."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "A child with a deceleration injury and a negative urinalysis can still have a major renal injury (UPJ avulsion — no urine reaches the bladder). Don't be reassured by a clean UA."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Solid-organ grading: spleen I–V (I–III repair/observe, IV–V remove); liver I–VI; renal I–V with hematuria = collecting-system reached."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A radiologist's report on a trauma CT will say only 'Grade III splenic injury,' not a paragraph. Why is the grade enough to drive your decision — and where is the cutoff between 'fix or watch' and 'remove'?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe pancreatic, pelvic, and thoracoabdominal trauma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Rose closes fast and by anecdote, so keep this tight. The pancreas is a crush injury: lying retroperitoneally across the spine, a focal midline blow can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column — his garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine, repaired with a Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy. Work it up with amylase and lipase (also checked in lavage fluid), see it on CT/ultrasound, and use ERCP to define the ductal anatomy; expect severe back pain because there's no room in the retroperitoneum. Thoracoabdominal and pelvic trauma in a crashing multi-trauma patient is a team approach through a thoracoabdominal incision, working chest and abdomen at once."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DPL IS HISTORICAL; REBOA BUYS TIME. Diagnostic peritoneal lavage once answered 'is there blood, bile, fecal material, bacteria, or amylase in the belly?' — but CT answers those quickly, so lavage is now mostly of historical interest (still used where imaging is unavailable). REBOA is the newer temporizing tool: a balloon occludes the aorta to control hemorrhage, but only in certain zones — never across the renal-artery segment, which would cause renal ischemia. It buys minutes for resuscitation; it is a bridge, not a repair."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pancreas = crush/transection over the spine; work up with amylase/lipase and ERCP (ductal anatomy)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "DPL is largely historical (CT replaced it); REBOA temporizes — only in safe aortic zones."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Scanning the unstable patient. A hypotensive trauma patient with a positive FAST goes straight to the OR, not to CT — stability, not the organ, drives disposition. CT is only for the patient you can stabilize. → LO 37.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Reading maroon/entry point as the injury. For penetrating trauma the trajectory is the injury; a sub-nipple wound can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because it rides up on expiration. → LO 37.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Calling Kehr's sign abdominal pain. Kehr's sign is LEFT-SHOULDER pain (referred diaphragmatic irritation from splenic blood), the prof's explicit board flag — not localized belly pain. → LO 37.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Removing every injured spleen. Grades I–III repair or observe (especially in children, to avoid OPSI from encapsulated bacteria); only IV–V (crush/bisection/shattered) come out. → LO 37.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Trusting a negative UA in a child. A pediatric UPJ avulsion after deceleration can give a NEGATIVE urinalysis because no urine reaches the bladder — image the child anyway. → LO 37.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Putting the REBOA balloon anywhere. REBOA occludes the aorta only in certain zones — never across the renal arteries, which would cause renal ischemia. It temporizes; it does not repair. → LO 37.5"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"hypotensive, tense abdomen, positive FAST\" → to the OR, not the scanner. Scan only if they stabilize."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"stab wound just below the left nipple\" → think diaphragm + spleen; trace the trajectory, not the entry point."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"splenic injury with left-shoulder pain and hiccups\" → Kehr's sign (the board answer)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"stable child with an isolated splenic laceration\" → save the spleen (observe in ICU); avoid OPSI."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"child, deceleration, flank pain, clean urinalysis\" → still suspect UPJ avulsion; a negative UA doesn't clear it."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"balloon inflated to control aortic hemorrhage\" → REBOA, and only in a safe zone (not across the renals)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Traumatic injury of the liver, biliary tree, and pancreas — the elective-surgical counterparts of these same organs are in Lec 45-46 (Surgical Aspects of the Gallbladder & Biliary Tract / Liver & Pancreas)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Hemodynamic stability deciding OR vs imaging echoes the GI-bleed logic — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), prior doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — FAST/CT and amylase/lipase reasoning for the acute abdomen carries into Lec 38 (Abdominal Pain / Diverticulitis), this doc"}]}]}, "38": {"prof": "Dr. R. Jackeline Moljo", "tldr": "Don't confuse diverticulOSIS (the pouches) with diverticulITIS (inflamed pouches): CT with contrast confirms it, most uncomplicated cases need no antibiotics, and the Hinchey stage decides who goes to surgery.", "mustKnows": ["1. CT is the study of choice. CT of the abdomen and pelvis with oral and IV contrast is the imaging study of choice for acute diverticulitis — sensitivity 94%, specificity 99%. It looks for localized bowel-wall thickening (>4 mm), pericolonic fat stranding, and diverticula, and it stages the complications (abscess, obstruction, fistula, free air).", "2. Water-soluble contrast, never barium. If perforation is suspected, any contrast study uses a water-soluble medium — never barium. Leaked barium causes barium peritonitis; water-soluble contrast is harmlessly absorbed. Moljo flagged this twice: \"if there's a perforation and we use barium… very big trouble.\"", "3. Uncomplicated diverticulitis usually needs NO antibiotics. For uncomplicated diverticulitis in a reliable, immunocompetent outpatient, manage with a clear-then-low-fiber diet and analgesia — antibiotics are usually not required. When abx are used, a fluoroquinolone or TMP-SMX must be paired with metronidazole for anaerobes (amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone).", "4. Abscess size sets the move: 4 cm. A diverticular abscess <4 cm is treated with antibiotics alone; one ≥4 cm gets CT-guided percutaneous drainage. Separately, microperforation (contained — air bubbles, no extraluminal contrast) is managed nonoperatively in ~94%, while frank perforation with feculent peritonitis mandates emergency surgery.", "5. Hinchey stages it; obstruction is the #1 complication. The modified Hinchey classification (0–IV) is CT-based — zero is good, four is bad — and stages III/IV (purulent or fecal peritonitis) drive surgery. The most common complication is obstruction, then perforation, then abscess.", "6. A colonic diverticulum is a PSEUDOdiverticulum; recurrence climbs. A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum — it herniates mucosa/submucosa through the wall but does not include all layers. After a first attack, recurrence is 33%; after a second, 66%. Colonoscopy is done 6–8 weeks AFTER resolution, never during the acute attack."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "List the appropriate history questions needed for a patient with diverticulitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "ANATOMY FIRST. Moljo built the whole lecture around a single ED vignette — a 68-year-old woman with three days of left-lower-quadrant pain, low-grade fever and chills — and her one repeated instruction is to start with anatomy: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Name what lives in the painful quadrant (sigmoid colon, ovary, bladder) and the history questions write themselves. The classic tell is constant LLQ pain with fever; ask too about timing, change in bowel habits, urinary symptoms, and — in a woman — gynecologic causes, which is why she argued the declined pelvic exam still leaves a real gap (an ovarian source can masquerade as colonic pain). Notice the exam targets recognition here, not deep recall — you are pattern-matching a presentation, not memorizing a checklist."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TWO CLUES WORTH ASKING ABOUT. First, the fistula screen: pneumaturia (air in the urine) and fecaluria (stool in the urine) point to a colovesical fistula between the inflamed colon and the bladder — a complication you only catch if you ask. Second, the dietary myth Moljo defended twice under student questioning: patients with diverticular disease do not need to avoid nuts, seeds, corn, or popcorn — \"we don't have to tell them not to eat those things.\" The genuine dietary risk is red meat (six or more servings a week) on a low-fiber background; she noted the meat data was specific to red meat, with chicken and fish fine."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pneumaturia + fecaluria = colovesical fistula."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Seeds/nuts/corn/popcorn do NOT raise risk; red meat (≥6/wk) does."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe which tests are necessary to distinguish between the differential diagnoses in a patient with diverticulitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The workup runs on one idea Moljo built into a quiz slide: each test answers a specific question, and you order it to confirm a suspicion rather than to fish. The lab panel sorts the differential — CBC (infection? anemia from a GI bleed?), CMP (diabetes, electrolytes, and crucially renal function before contrast), CRP/ESR (inflammation), urinalysis and culture (UTI, the LLQ mimic), HCG (pregnancy in any woman of childbearing age), and blood cultures if she looks septic. Two of those — the CMP renal check and the HCG — exist specifically to make it safe to give contrast."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CT IS THE STUDY OF CHOICE. CT of the abdomen and pelvis with oral and IV contrast is the imaging study of choice for acute diverticulitis, and the numbers are worth knowing cold: sensitivity 94%, specificity 99%. The high specificity is what makes a positive scan confirmatory. Look for the triad of localized bowel-wall thickening (>4 mm), pericolonic fat stranding from inflammation, and the diverticula themselves — and the same scan stages the complications (abscess, obstruction, fistula, free air), which is exactly why it feeds straight into the Hinchey system and the management decisions in LO 38.4."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CT abd/pelvis with oral + IV contrast = study of choice; Se 94 / Sp 99."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CT triad: wall thickening >4 mm + pericolonic fat stranding + diverticula."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WATER-SOLUBLE CONTRAST, NEVER BARIUM. If a perforation is suspected and any contrast study is used, the contrast must be a water-soluble medium — never barium. The mechanism is the whole point: water-soluble contrast that leaks into the peritoneum is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes barium peritonitis, a severe chemical inflammatory reaction. Moljo hit this twice and with weight — if there is a perforation and you use barium, \"very big trouble.\" This is the single most quotable test-selection rule in the lecture."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Suspected perforation → water-soluble contrast, never barium (barium peritonitis)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE OTHER MODALITIES, AND WHY CT WINS. Ultrasound can show a hypoechoic peridiverticular reaction and segmental wall thickening, but it is operator-dependent and less reliable — Moljo called it easy to do but inferior. MRI matches CT's anatomy and spares radiation, but it is slower and costlier and lacks the validated diverticulitis criteria CT carries. Plain abdominal films (supine and upright) are a screen for air-fluid levels, obstruction, and free air, not a confirmatory test. When the question asks how you distinguish diverticulitis from its mimics, the answer is the contrast CT."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Water-soluble contrast, never barium, when perforation is on the table — leaked barium causes barium peritonitis. Water-soluble contrast is simply absorbed."}, {"t": "key", "x": "CT abd/pelvis with oral + IV contrast is the study of choice (Se 94 / Sp 99) — it both confirms the diagnosis and stages the complications for Hinchey."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "In a woman of childbearing age, gate the contrast: check renal function (CMP) and an HCG before the scan."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Your patient may have a perforation and needs a contrast study. Which contrast do you choose, and what is the specific disaster you are avoiding?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Describe the clinical presentation and management of diverticulosis versus diverticulitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "THE DEFINITIONS LADDER. The whole LO turns on keeping four terms straight, so climb the ladder deliberately. A diverticulum is a single sac-like outpouching of colonic mucosa through a weak point in the muscular wall; diverticula is just the plural. DiverticulOSIS is the presence of diverticula — often asymptomatic. DiverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which is then subdivided into uncomplicated versus complicated (abscess, fistula, obstruction, or free perforation). Diverticular disease is the umbrella term for clinically significant, symptomatic disease — including diverticulitis, diverticular bleeding, and segmental colitis. The exam loves to swap osis and itis on you, so anchor it: -osis = the pouches, -itis = the pouches inflamed."}, {"t": "p", "x": "A COLONIC DIVERTICULUM IS A PSEUDODIVERTICULUM. This is the slide's one mechanistic nuance and a clean board point. A colonic diverticulum herniates only the mucosa and submucosa through gaps in the muscular wall (typically where vasa recta penetrate) — it does not include all the colonic layers, so \"in reality it is a pseudodiverticulum.\" A true diverticulum would contain the full wall thickness. That same vessel-adjacent weak point is why the pouches bleed, which is the bridge to the diverticulOSIS painless-bleed story from the endoscopy lecture."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "-osis = diverticula present; -itis = diverticula inflamed (uncomplicated vs complicated)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum — mucosa/submucosa only, not all layers."}, {"t": "p", "x": "EPIDEMIOLOGY BY AGE, SEX, AND SIDE. DiverticulOSIS is fundamentally a disease of aging: US prevalence rises from under 20% at age 40 to about 60% by age 60, with the number and size of diverticula climbing too. In Western countries the disease is left-sided (sigmoid); Asian people and Pacific Islanders skew toward proximal (right-sided) disease that is often congenital — a point a student confirmed from a rotation in Asia, where the diverticulosis ran right-sided. The sex pattern flips with age: under 50 it is more common in men, with a female preponderance after 50 that becomes marked over 70. As for how often osis turns into trouble — diverticulitis hits ~1–2% of the general population and ~4% of those with diverticulosis, and bleeding occurs in 3–5%."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Diverticulosis prevalence: <20% at 40 → ~60% at 60; Western = left, Asian = proximal/right."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MANAGEMENT SPLITS WITH THE NAME. Treat diverticulOSIS by modifying risk factors only — diet, exercise, weight, alcohol, smoking — there is no drug for the pouches themselves. DiverticulITIS management depends on severity and complications, and that full decision tree (outpatient versus admission, antibiotics or not, abscess thresholds, surgery) is the work of LO 38.4."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "DiverticulOSIS = the pouches (often asymptomatic, the painless-bleed source); diverticulITIS = the pouches inflamed (LLQ pain + fever). Same anatomy, different word and different disease."}, {"t": "key", "x": "A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum: it herniates mucosa/submucosa but not all wall layers — and it forms at the vessel-weak point, which is why these pouches bleed."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Side and population are a clue: Western diverticulosis is left-sided; Asian/Pacific patients skew proximal/right-sided and often congenital."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A diverticulum, diverticulOSIS, diverticulITIS, and diverticular disease are four different words. Define each, and say which one is a pseudodiverticulum and why."}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the management of diverticulitis, its prognosis, and resultant complications", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — UNCOMPLICATED VS COMPLICATED. Every management decision forks on one split: uncomplicated diverticulitis (inflammation only) is managed medically, often outpatient; complicated disease (abscess, perforation, obstruction, fistula) needs a more aggressive, usually inpatient and sometimes surgical approach. The modern, high-yield shift lives on the uncomplicated side — and the entire complication ladder lives on the other."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ANTIBIOTIC SHIFT. Antibiotics were long the mainstay, but European trials consistently show that uncomplicated diverticulitis usually does NOT need them. For a selected patient — immunocompetent, reliable for follow-up, no systemic disturbance — manage with a clear diet for 2–3 days advancing to low fiber, acetaminophen and antispasmodics for pain, and close follow-up. Moljo was candid that this is a hard habit to break: \"it's very hard for us physicians to stop doing that,\" but \"we really don't need antibiotics for uncomplicated diverticulitis.\" Reserve antibiotics for patients with major comorbidities, immunocompromise, immunomodulating drugs, or signs of systemic disturbance."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN YOU DO TREAT — COVER ANAEROBES. When antibiotics are indicated, give 7–10 days of broad-spectrum oral coverage spanning aerobes and anaerobes. The trap is the anaerobe gap: a fluoroquinolone or TMP-SMX does NOT cover anaerobes, so each must be paired with metronidazole (or clindamycin if metronidazole isn't tolerated). Amoxicillin-clavulanate is the single-agent option because it already covers both. Moljo drove this as a rhetorical quiz — what does metronidazole cover? Anaerobes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Uncomplicated + reliable + immunocompetent → no antibiotics; diet + analgesia + follow-up."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Fluoroquinolone or TMP-SMX + metronidazole (anaerobes); amox-clav covers both alone."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ADMIT WHEN. Hospitalize if CT shows complicated disease, or if CT shows uncomplicated disease but the patient carries a high-risk feature: sepsis/SIRS (temp >38°C or <36°C, HR >90, RR >20, WBC >12,000 or <4,000, CRP >15), severe pain that can't be controlled below 5/10 in the ED, age >70, significant comorbidities, immunosuppression, intolerance of oral intake (obstruction/ileus), or unreliability for follow-up (e.g., no support system). Inpatients get IV antibiotics against gram-negative rods and anaerobes, IV fluids, analgesia, and NPO for bowel rest, then advance the diet; they discharge on oral antibiotics to finish a 10–14 day course."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE COMPLICATIONS, AND THE TWO THRESHOLDS THAT MATTER. First, perforation comes in two flavors. Frank perforation — free air under the diaphragm with feculent diffuse peritonitis — is life-threatening and mandates emergency surgery. Microperforation (contained — small air bubbles but no extraluminal contrast) is treated with IV antibiotics, and ~94% are managed nonoperatively. Second, the abscess 4-cm rule: an abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage added (surgery only if drainage fails or the collection is inaccessible). A fistula (colovesical, colovaginal, and others) is managed surgically."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Frank perforation → emergency surgery; microperforation → IV abx, ~94% nonoperative."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HINCHEY STAGES IT; III/IV GO TO SURGERY. The modified Hinchey classification (0–IV) is CT-based and guides intervention. Moljo de-emphasized rote memorization — \"you don't need to memorize this… zero is good and four is bad\" — but know the shape: 0 = mild (wall thickening); I = pericolic phlegmon/abscess; II = distant/pelvic abscess; III = generalized purulent peritonitis; IV = generalized fecal peritonitis. The operational point is that stages III and IV drive surgery, along with uncontrolled sepsis, a ruptured abscess, an undrainable abscess, fistula, obstruction/stricture, and failed medical therapy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Hinchey / What it is / Move): 0 — Mild diverticulitis (wall thickening on CT) · Medical, often outpatient ; I — Pericolic/mesocolic phlegmon or abscess · Antibiotics; drain if abscess ≥4 cm ; II — Distant (pelvic/retroperitoneal) abscess · Antibiotics + percutaneous drainage ; III — Generalized PURULENT peritonitis · Surgery ; IV — Generalized FECAL peritonitis · Surgery"}, {"t": "p", "x": "PROGNOSIS AND THE FOLLOW-UP SCOPE. Recurrence climbs with each attack: 33% after a first episode, 66% after a second (rebleeding up to ~6%). Among complications, obstruction is the most common, followed by perforation, then abscess. Younger patients can paradoxically have more severe disease, often from delayed diagnosis, and immunocompromised patients carry markedly higher morbidity and mortality. Finally, the timing rule the exam loves: perform colonoscopy 6–8 WEEKS after the attack resolves (the slide says weeks; the transcript's \"hours\" is a transcription slip) — never during the acute attack, when scoping the inflamed colon risks perforation. The point of the delayed scope is to exclude colorectal cancer or other pathology, especially in a younger first-time patient."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Recurrence 33% after 1st episode, 66% after 2nd; obstruction = most common complication."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Colonoscopy 6–8 weeks AFTER resolution, never during the acute attack."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reflexively giving antibiotics for every diverticulitis — uncomplicated disease in a reliable, immunocompetent patient usually doesn't need them. And if you use a fluoroquinolone/TMP-SMX, you must add metronidazole for anaerobes."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage. Frank perforation → emergency surgery; contained microperforation → IV abx."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Hinchey: zero good, four bad. Stages III (purulent) and IV (fecal) peritonitis are the ones that go to the OR."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Moljo says \"we really don't need antibiotics for uncomplicated diverticulitis\" — so when ARE antibiotics indicated, and when you do use a fluoroquinolone, what must you add and why?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. DiverticulOSIS vs diverticulITIS. They are different words for different diseases: -osis is the presence of pouches (often asymptomatic; the painless lower-GI bleeder from the endoscopy lecture), while -itis is the pouches inflamed (LLQ pain + fever). Don't let the exam swap them on you. → LO 38.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Barium when perforation is possible. If a perforation is suspected, any contrast study uses a water-soluble medium — leaked barium causes barium peritonitis. Water-soluble contrast is harmlessly absorbed. → LO 38.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Antibiotics for every diverticulitis. Uncomplicated disease in a reliable, immunocompetent patient usually needs no antibiotics — diet and analgesia suffice. Reserve abx for complicated disease or high-risk hosts. → LO 38.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. A fluoroquinolone alone covers diverticulitis. Fluoroquinolones and TMP-SMX don't cover anaerobes, so each must be paired with metronidazole (amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone). → LO 38.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. All abscesses get drained. The 4-cm rule: an abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; only ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage. → LO 38.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Scope during the acute attack. Colonoscopy is done 6–8 weeks AFTER resolution, never during the acute attack — scoping the inflamed colon risks perforation. Counsel away from the seeds/nuts myth too; red meat is the real dietary risk. → LO 38.1"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"painless large-volume rectal bleeding in a 70-year-old\" → think diverticulOSIS (the pouches bleeding), not the inflamed diverticulITIS."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"suspect perforation, ordering a contrast enema\" → water-soluble contrast, never barium (barium peritonitis)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"reliable young patient, CT shows uncomplicated diverticulitis\" → no antibiotics; clear→low-fiber diet, analgesia, close follow-up."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"started on ciprofloxacin for diverticulitis\" → add metronidazole for anaerobes (or use amox-clavulanate alone)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"CT shows a 5 cm pericolic abscess\" → CT-guided percutaneous drainage plus antibiotics (≥4 cm)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"first diverticulitis, never scoped, now recovered\" → colonoscopy 6–8 weeks later to exclude cancer; not during the attack."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — diverticulOSIS (painless lower-GI bleed, #1 cause >50, self-limits ~80%) vs this lecture's diverticulITIS — the explicit osis-vs-itis hinge — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), the 31-34 doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Colonoscopy timing & CRC screening (the 6-8-week post-resolution scope to exclude cancer) — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), the 31-34 doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Surgical management of complicated lower-GI disease (abscess drainage, resection) — also Lec 45-46 (Surgical Aspects of the Liver, Biliary Tract & Pancreas)"}]}]}};
const LECTURE_REFERENCES = {};

// QUIZ_START
const QUIZ = [[31, "Infectious Diarrhea (Lec 31–32)", [[1, "Recognize the etiology of common infectious diarrheas", [["A traveler returns with profuse, voluminous, watery, non-bloody diarrhea and rapid dehydration. The most likely organism is:", ["Enterotoxigenic E. coli", "Enterohemorrhagic E. coli", "Shigella sonnei", "Campylobacter jejuni", "Salmonella typhi"], 0, "Voluminous watery non-bloody stools with rapid dehydration is the secretory pattern. ETEC is the classic traveler's-diarrhea enterotoxin producer; cholera is the other archetype.\n\nWhy not — Enterohemorrhagic E. coli: EHEC is inflammatory — bloody stools and HUS, not voluminous watery.  Shigella sonnei: Shigella is inflammatory dysentery — bloody, mucoid, febrile.  Campylobacter jejuni: Campylobacter is inflammatory and often poultry-linked, not secretory.  Salmonella typhi: Salmonella typhi is inflammatory/systemic, not a watery secretory bug.", "advanced"], ["Clostridioides difficile damages colonic cells through which type of toxin?", ["Cytotoxin", "Neurotoxin", "Endotoxin", "Enterotoxin", "Superantigen"], 0, "C. difficile produces cytotoxins (toxins A/B) that damage colonic mucosa. Blavo self-corrected in lecture: the neurotoxin producer is C. botulinum, not C. difficile.\n\nWhy not — Neurotoxin: Neurotoxin is C. botulinum (botulism), which damages nerves.  Endotoxin: Endotoxin is LPS released on gram-negative cell death, not a C. diff product.  Enterotoxin: Enterotoxins (cholera, Staph) act on the gut surface to drive secretion.  Superantigen: Superantigens drive massive T-cell activation, not C. diff colitis.", "basic"], ["Bloody diarrhea from E. coli O157:H7 progresses to renal failure, hemolysis, and thrombocytopenia. The complication is:", ["Hemolytic uremic syndrome", "Disseminated intravascular coagulation", "Reye syndrome", "Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura", "Guillain-Barré syndrome"], 0, "The classic triad — azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia — is hemolytic uremic syndrome, driven by the Shiga-like toxin of EHEC O157:H7.\n\nWhy not — Disseminated intravascular coagulation: DIC has consumptive coagulopathy with bleeding and abnormal coags, not the HUS triad.  Reye syndrome: Reye syndrome is salicylate-associated hepatic/cerebral injury, not an O157:H7 sequela.  Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura: TTP shares MAHA but is ADAMTS13-related with neuro signs and fever, not O157:H7.  Guillain-Barré syndrome: Guillain-Barré (ascending paralysis) follows Campylobacter, not O157:H7.", "basic"], ["An endotoxin that triggers inflammation only when the bacterium dies is best described as the:", ["Lipopolysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria", "Exotoxin of gram-positive bacteria", "Secreted protein of gram-positive bacteria", "Capsular polysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria", "Teichoic acid of gram-positive bacteria"], 0, "Endotoxin is the lipopolysaccharide (LPS) of the gram-negative outer membrane, released on cell lysis to trigger inflammation — distinct from secreted exotoxins.\n\nWhy not — Exotoxin of gram-positive bacteria: Exotoxins are actively secreted, not released only on death.  Secreted protein of gram-positive bacteria: Secreted proteins are exotoxins, released by living bacteria.  Capsular polysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria: Capsular polysaccharide is an anti-phagocytic coat, not endotoxin.  Teichoic acid of gram-positive bacteria: Teichoic acid is a gram-positive wall component, not LPS.", "basic"]]], [2, "Identify the clinical presentations of common infectious diarrheas", [["Greasy, malodorous, non-bloody stools with fat malabsorption most suggest:", ["Giardia duodenalis", "Shigella sonnei", "Enterohemorrhagic E. coli", "Vibrio cholerae", "Salmonella typhi"], 0, "Giardia trophozoites line the mucosa and blunt fat absorption, producing oily, foul-smelling, non-bloody stools — the classic osmotic/malabsorptive picture.\n\nWhy not — Shigella sonnei: Shigella is bloody inflammatory dysentery, not greasy malabsorption.  Enterohemorrhagic E. coli: EHEC is bloody and inflammatory, not fatty.  Vibrio cholerae: Cholera is voluminous watery secretory, not greasy.  Salmonella typhi: Salmonella is inflammatory/systemic, not a malabsorptive picture.", "basic"], ["Frequent moderate-volume bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes and fever indicate which diarrhea type?", ["Inflammatory diarrhea", "Secretory diarrhea", "Osmotic diarrhea", "Factitious diarrhea", "Functional diarrhea"], 0, "Blood, mucus, fecal leukocytes, and fever signal mucosal invasion/damage — the inflammatory pattern (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter).\n\nWhy not — Secretory diarrhea: Secretory diarrhea is voluminous watery and non-bloody, without leukocytes.  Osmotic diarrhea: Osmotic diarrhea is non-bloody and resolves with fasting.  Factitious diarrhea: Factitious (laxative) diarrhea lacks blood and fecal leukocytes.  Functional diarrhea: Functional diarrhea has no inflammatory markers or fever.", "basic"], ["Which finding most specifically signals dehydration in an infant?", ["Sunken anterior fontanelle", "Bulging anterior fontanelle", "Brisk capillary refill", "Increased skin turgor", "Excessive tearing"], 0, "A sunken anterior fontanelle reflects reduced body fluid (dehydration); a bulging fontanelle reflects raised intracranial pressure (e.g., meningitis) — the opposite concern.\n\nWhy not — Bulging anterior fontanelle: A bulging fontanelle suggests raised ICP, not dehydration.  Brisk capillary refill: Brisk capillary refill is normal perfusion, not dehydration.  Increased skin turgor: Dehydration decreases skin turgor; it does not increase it.  Excessive tearing: Reduced (not excessive) tearing accompanies dehydration.", "basic"], ["A child vomits for two to three days before watery diarrhea begins. The most likely agent is:", ["Rotavirus", "Vibrio cholerae", "Giardia duodenalis", "Enterotoxigenic E. coli", "Entamoeba histolytica"], 0, "Rotavirus characteristically causes several days of vomiting before watery diarrhea — Blavo's point that the vomiting-to-diarrhea sequence distinguishes one case from another.\n\nWhy not — Vibrio cholerae: Cholera presents with abrupt voluminous watery diarrhea, not a vomiting prodrome.  Giardia duodenalis: Giardia is subacute greasy diarrhea, not a vomiting prodrome.  Enterotoxigenic E. coli: ETEC is acute traveler's watery diarrhea without the prodrome.  Entamoeba histolytica: E. histolytica causes dysentery/abscesses, not a vomiting prodrome.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Recognize the differential diagnosis of common infectious diarrhea", [["Compared with osmotic diarrhea, secretory diarrhea is characterized by:", ["Voluminous watery stools that persist with fasting", "Small-volume stools that resolve with fasting", "Bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes", "Greasy stools with prominent fat malabsorption", "Stools driven by a high stool osmotic gap"], 0, "Secretory diarrhea is enterotoxin-driven active secretion: voluminous, watery, and it continues even when the patient stops eating. Osmotic diarrhea depends on ingested solute and stops with fasting.\n\nWhy not — Small-volume stools that resolve with fasting: Resolving with fasting is the osmotic pattern.  Bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes: Blood and leukocytes define inflammatory, not secretory, diarrhea.  Greasy stools with prominent fat malabsorption: Greasy malabsorptive stool is the osmotic/Giardia pattern.  Stools driven by a high stool osmotic gap: A high osmotic gap defines osmotic, not secretory, diarrhea.", "basic"], ["A traveler has one week of greasy, foul-smelling, non-bloody diarrhea with bloating; one stool O&P is negative. The best read is:", ["Giardia, and repeat stool ova-and-parasite testing", "ETEC, and give oral rehydration salts", "Vibrio cholerae, and start IV crystalloid", "Norovirus, and simply reassure the patient", "EHEC, and strictly avoid all antibiotics"], 0, "Greasy, malodorous, bloating, subacute non-bloody diarrhea after travel is Giardia. A single O&P is insensitive — repeat it up to three times before excluding the parasite.\n\nWhy not — ETEC, and give oral rehydration salts: ETEC is acute voluminous watery diarrhea, not greasy and bloating.  Vibrio cholerae, and start IV crystalloid: Cholera is voluminous watery secretory, not greasy malabsorption.  Norovirus, and simply reassure the patient: Norovirus is acute self-limited vomiting/diarrhea, not weeks of greasy stool.  EHEC, and strictly avoid all antibiotics: EHEC is bloody inflammatory diarrhea, not greasy non-bloody.", "advanced"], ["A patient has profuse watery non-bloody diarrhea with severe dehydration and no fever. The priority intervention is:", ["Aggressive fluid and electrolyte replacement", "Empiric oral ciprofloxacin therapy", "Loperamide to slow gut motility", "Bismuth subsalicylate for symptoms", "Stool culture before any treatment"], 0, "This is the secretory/cholera-like pattern; the immediate threat is fluid and electrolyte loss, so rehydration comes first — diagnostics and drugs do not precede resuscitation.\n\nWhy not — Empiric oral ciprofloxacin therapy: Empiric antibiotics are not first-line and can harm (e.g., O157:H7).  Loperamide to slow gut motility: Antimotility agents are used with caution and don't treat dehydration.  Bismuth subsalicylate for symptoms: Bismuth treats symptoms, not the life-threatening fluid loss.  Stool culture before any treatment: Culture doesn't change the immediate need to rehydrate.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Identify the workup of infectious diarrheas", [["Which feature most justifies a diagnostic work-up rather than observation alone?", ["Bloody stools with high fever", "Two days of mild watery stools", "A single loose stool after travel", "Self-limited nausea without diarrhea", "Normal vital signs and good hydration"], 0, "Bloody stools plus high fever flags an inflammatory/invasive process and the need for testing. Mild, brief, well-hydrated cases are observed, not worked up.\n\nWhy not — Two days of mild watery stools: Mild brief watery stools are observed, not investigated.  A single loose stool after travel: A single loose stool needs no work-up.  Self-limited nausea without diarrhea: Nausea without diarrhea is not an indication to test stool.  Normal vital signs and good hydration: Normal vitals and hydration argue against work-up.", "basic"], ["Which stool test most reliably confirms intestinal inflammation?", ["Fecal calprotectin", "Fecal leukocytes", "Stool guaiac", "Stool osmotic gap", "Urine specific gravity"], 0, "Stool calprotectin (and lactoferrin) are leukocyte proteins that detect intestinal inflammation more reliably than the older fecal-leukocyte smear.\n\nWhy not — Fecal leukocytes: Fecal leukocytes are less sensitive/reliable than calprotectin.  Stool guaiac: Guaiac detects occult blood, not inflammation per se.  Stool osmotic gap: The osmotic gap separates osmotic from secretory, not inflammation.  Urine specific gravity: Urine specific gravity gauges hydration, not gut inflammation.", "basic"], ["A stool osmotic gap above 160 mOsm/kg most supports which diarrhea type?", ["Osmotic diarrhea", "Secretory diarrhea", "Inflammatory diarrhea", "Bacillary dysentery", "Antibiotic-associated colitis"], 0, "A high stool osmotic gap means an unabsorbed osmotically active solute is driving water into the lumen — the definition of osmotic diarrhea. Secretory diarrhea has a low gap.\n\nWhy not — Secretory diarrhea: Secretory diarrhea has a LOW osmotic gap (electrolyte-driven).  Inflammatory diarrhea: Inflammatory diarrhea is defined by blood/leukocytes, not the gap.  Bacillary dysentery: Dysentery is inflammatory, characterized by blood, not the gap.  Antibiotic-associated colitis: C. diff colitis is inflammatory, not gap-defined.", "advanced"], ["A urine specific gravity above 1.020 with an elevated BUN most suggests:", ["Dehydration", "Overhydration", "Active GI bleeding", "Bacterial coinfection", "Lactose intolerance"], 0, "Concentrated urine (SG >1.020) and a rising BUN are markers of volume depletion — Blavo's point that the test confirms the dehydration you already suspect.\n\nWhy not — Overhydration: Overhydration produces dilute urine and a low-normal BUN.  Active GI bleeding: GI bleeding is suggested by guaiac/hematochezia, not urine SG.  Bacterial coinfection: Coinfection is suggested by leukocytosis, not urine concentration.  Lactose intolerance: Lactose intolerance relates to the osmotic gap, not urine SG.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Recognize the management of common infectious diarrheas, including fluid and electrolyte management (ORS, IV)", [["Oral rehydration solution works primarily because glucose drives absorption of:", ["Sodium and water across the gut", "Potassium and water across the gut", "Chloride against its electrochemical gradient", "Bicarbonate into the intestinal lumen", "Protein across the mucosal barrier"], 0, "ORS exploits glucose-coupled sodium cotransport (SGLT1): glucose pulls sodium in, and water follows osmotically — which is why ORS needs both glucose and sodium.\n\nWhy not — Potassium and water across the gut: Cotransport is glucose-SODIUM, not glucose-potassium.  Chloride against its electrochemical gradient: Chloride is not the cotransported species in SGLT1.  Bicarbonate into the intestinal lumen: Bicarbonate secretion is not the ORS mechanism.  Protein across the mucosal barrier: Protein is not cotransported with glucose for rehydration.", "basic"], ["Why are sodas and fruit juices poor rehydration fluids in diarrhea?", ["Glucose far exceeds sodium content", "Sodium far exceeds glucose content", "They are essentially isotonic fluids", "They contain excessive potassium content", "They contain no usable carbohydrate"], 0, "Sodas/juices have glucose vastly exceeding sodium; the unbalanced osmotic load lacks the sodium needed for cotransport and can pull more water into the lumen, worsening losses.\n\nWhy not — Sodium far exceeds glucose content: It's the reverse — glucose exceeds sodium in these drinks.  They are essentially isotonic fluids: They are hyperosmolar, not isotonic.  They contain excessive potassium content: Excess potassium is not the issue; the glucose:sodium ratio is.  They contain no usable carbohydrate: They contain plenty of carbohydrate — that's the problem.", "basic"], ["When is intravenous rehydration preferred over oral rehydration?", ["Persistent vomiting with severe dehydration", "Mild dehydration tolerating oral fluids", "Mild vomiting without bowel obstruction", "A stable child drinking fluids well", "Self-limited mild watery diarrhea"], 0, "IV is reserved for when ORT is not feasible or safe — persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, or aspiration risk. Mild vomiting alone is not a contraindication to ORS.\n\nWhy not — Mild dehydration tolerating oral fluids: Mild dehydration tolerating fluids is treated orally.  Mild vomiting without bowel obstruction: Mild vomiting without obstruction still allows ORS.  A stable child drinking fluids well: A child drinking well does not need IV.  Self-limited mild watery diarrhea: Self-limited mild diarrhea needs oral fluids at most.", "basic"], ["Bismuth subsalicylate is avoided in children under 17 because of the risk for:", ["Reye syndrome", "Hemolytic uremic syndrome", "Serotonin syndrome", "Clostridioides difficile colitis", "Lactic acidosis"], 0, "Bismuth subsalicylate contains a salicylate; in children/teens this carries Reye-syndrome risk — Blavo notes it is a frequent exam point.\n\nWhy not — Hemolytic uremic syndrome: HUS is the O157:H7 sequela, not a bismuth effect.  Serotonin syndrome: Serotonin syndrome is a serotonergic-drug effect, unrelated.  Clostridioides difficile colitis: C. diff colitis follows broad antibiotics, not bismuth.  Lactic acidosis: Lactic acidosis is not the bismuth concern in children.", "advanced"], ["A child with bloody diarrhea and confirmed E. coli O157:H7 should NOT receive antibiotics because they:", ["Increase hemolytic uremic syndrome risk", "Meaningfully shorten the diarrheal illness", "Reliably eradicate the Shiga toxin", "Completely prevent further fecal shedding", "Have no effect on the clinical course"], 0, "Antibiotics can increase Shiga-toxin release and the risk of HUS in O157:H7, so they are withheld; fluids and supportive care are the mainstay.\n\nWhy not — Meaningfully shorten the diarrheal illness: Antibiotics do not reliably shorten the illness here.  Reliably eradicate the Shiga toxin: They do not eradicate the toxin — they can increase its release.  Completely prevent further fecal shedding: They do not reliably stop shedding (and can prolong Salmonella carriage).  Have no effect on the clinical course: They are not neutral — they are potentially harmful.", "advanced"]]]]], [33, "GI Endoscopy (Lec 33–34)", [[1, "Describe the role of endoscopic procedures for GI hemorrhage", [["A patient pumps out large-volume maroon stool and is hemodynamically unstable. The most important source to exclude FIRST is:", ["A brisk upper GI source moving fast", "Internal hemorrhoids of the rectum", "Diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon", "Angiodysplasia of the cecum", "Ischemic colitis of the splenic flexure"], 0, "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) is the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed — and, unlike most lower sources, you can stop it endoscopically. Exclude it first.\n\nWhy not — Internal hemorrhoids of the rectum: Hemorrhoids cause small-volume bright-red bleeding, not unstable maroon stool.  Diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon: Diverticulosis bleeds but is the answer for painless STABLE elderly hematochezia.  Angiodysplasia of the cecum: Angiodysplasia usually weeps slowly, rarely causing instability first.  Ischemic colitis of the splenic flexure: Ischemic colitis causes pain and bloody diarrhea, not brisk maroon exsanguination.", "advanced"], ["Endoscopic therapy to STOP active bleeding is far more effective for:", ["Upper GI bleeding lesions", "Lower GI bleeding lesions", "Cecal vascular ectasias", "Diverticular bleeding sites", "Small-bowel angiodysplasias"], 0, "The therapeutic potential of endoscopy is much greater for UPPER pathology (clip an ulcer vessel, band varices); lower-GI bleeding has limited endoscopic therapy.\n\nWhy not — Lower GI bleeding lesions: Lower-GI bleeding has limited endoscopic therapeutic options.  Cecal vascular ectasias: Cecal ectasias are lower-tract lesions with limited durable therapy.  Diverticular bleeding sites: Diverticular bleeding usually stops on its own; endoscopic control is limited.  Small-bowel angiodysplasias: Small-bowel AVMs are hard to reach and treat durably.", "basic"], ["Why is an IV proton pump inhibitor given for an acute bleeding ulcer?", ["Raising gastric pH stabilizes the clot", "It directly cauterizes the bleeding vessel", "It replaces the lost circulating volume", "It rapidly reverses anticoagulation", "It immediately eradicates Helicobacter pylori"], 0, "Clot stability depends on pH and platelets; acutely raising gastric pH toward neutral lets the clot hold while you arrange endoscopy.\n\nWhy not — It directly cauterizes the bleeding vessel: The PPI doesn't cauterize — endoscopic clips/thermal therapy do.  It replaces the lost circulating volume: Volume is replaced with fluids/blood, not a PPI.  It rapidly reverses anticoagulation: A PPI does not reverse anticoagulation.  It immediately eradicates Helicobacter pylori: H. pylori eradication takes a multi-drug course, not an acute PPI.", "basic"], ["Sudden massive bright-red hematemesis in a patient with cirrhosis is most likely from:", ["Esophageal varices", "A Mallory-Weiss tear", "Erosive gastritis", "A Schatzki ring", "Reflux esophagitis"], 0, "Portal hypertension from cirrhosis produces esophageal varices, which can bleed massively and painlessly — sometimes the presenting sign of unrecognized cirrhosis.\n\nWhy not — A Mallory-Weiss tear: A Mallory-Weiss tear is a benign, usually self-limited bleed after retching.  Erosive gastritis: Erosive gastritis oozes; it rarely causes massive variceal-type hemorrhage.  A Schatzki ring: A Schatzki ring causes dysphagia, not hemorrhage.  Reflux esophagitis: Reflux esophagitis bleeds little and isn't the cirrhosis association.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe the use of ERCP, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and wireless capsule endoscopy", [["A jaundiced patient has a pancreatic-head mass and no distant metastases. The best way to stage AND biopsy it is:", ["Endoscopic ultrasound", "ERCP with duct brushings", "Percutaneous CT-guided biopsy", "Wireless capsule endoscopy", "Upper endoscopy with biopsy"], 0, "EUS biopsies the mass through the stomach wall, assesses vascular involvement, and samples nodes — all in one staging procedure; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling.\n\nWhy not — ERCP with duct brushings: ERCP relieves obstruction; it rarely gets a tissue diagnosis of the mass.  Percutaneous CT-guided biopsy: Percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and may undersample.  Wireless capsule endoscopy: Capsule endoscopy cannot reach or biopsy the pancreas.  Upper endoscopy with biopsy: A forward-viewing EGD can't see or sample a mass behind the stomach.", "advanced"], ["Since the advent of MRCP, ERCP is reserved almost exclusively for:", ["Therapeutic relief of biliary obstruction", "Diagnosis of pancreatic masses", "Routine evaluation of abnormal liver tests", "Staging of esophageal cancer", "Screening for common-bile-duct stones"], 0, "ERCP is the most dangerous GI procedure; with MRCP available for diagnosis, ERCP is done to TREAT — sphincterotomy and stone extraction to relieve obstruction.\n\nWhy not — Diagnosis of pancreatic masses: Pancreatic masses are diagnosed by EUS, not ERCP.  Routine evaluation of abnormal liver tests: Abnormal liver tests are worked up noninvasively first.  Staging of esophageal cancer: Esophageal cancer is staged by EUS.  Screening for common-bile-duct stones: CBD stones are screened noninvasively with MRCP.", "basic"], ["Wireless capsule endoscopy is best suited for evaluating:", ["Occult bleeding of the small intestine", "Therapy of a bleeding duodenal ulcer", "Biopsy of a submucosal gastric mass", "Removal of a pedunculated colon polyp", "Staging of an early gastric cancer"], 0, "Capsule endoscopy is diagnostic-only and shines in the small bowel beyond scope reach; its #1 indication is occult GI bleeding (negative upper and lower), typically finding AVMs.\n\nWhy not — Therapy of a bleeding duodenal ulcer: The capsule cannot treat anything — it only takes pictures.  Biopsy of a submucosal gastric mass: It cannot biopsy a mass.  Removal of a pedunculated colon polyp: It cannot perform polypectomy.  Staging of an early gastric cancer: It cannot stage tumors or reliably image the stomach.", "basic"], ["Wireless capsule endoscopy is contraindicated in a patient with known:", ["Stricturing Crohn disease", "Iron-deficiency anemia", "Occult GI bleeding", "A prior negative colonoscopy", "Small-bowel angiodysplasia"], 0, "A stricture can trap the capsule, requiring surgical retrieval; known stricturing Crohn disease is a contraindication.\n\nWhy not — Iron-deficiency anemia: Iron-deficiency anemia is an indication, not a contraindication.  Occult GI bleeding: Occult GI bleeding is the #1 indication.  A prior negative colonoscopy: A prior negative colonoscopy is part of the occult-bleed workup, not a contraindication.  Small-bowel angiodysplasia: Angiodysplasia is exactly what capsule endoscopy looks for.", "advanced"]]], [3, "List the disease entities and endoscopic findings of the upper gastrointestinal tract", [["Barrett esophagus is a precursor to which malignancy?", ["Esophageal adenocarcinoma", "Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma", "Gastric adenocarcinoma", "Pancreatic adenocarcinoma", "Duodenal carcinoid tumor"], 0, "Barrett's (intestinal metaplasia from chronic reflux) is the precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus — not squamous cell carcinoma.\n\nWhy not — Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma: Squamous cell carcinoma arises in the UPPER esophagus, unrelated to Barrett's.  Gastric adenocarcinoma: Gastric adenocarcinoma is not the Barrett's sequela.  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma: Pancreatic cancer is unrelated to Barrett's.  Duodenal carcinoid tumor: Duodenal carcinoid is unrelated to Barrett's.", "basic"], ["Squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus classically arises in the:", ["Upper esophagus", "Lower esophagus", "Gastroesophageal junction", "Gastric antrum", "Duodenal bulb"], 0, "The upper esophagus gives squamous cell carcinoma; the lower esophagus (Barrett-associated) gives adenocarcinoma. The esophagus is 'tricky' precisely because the two split by location.\n\nWhy not — Lower esophagus: The lower esophagus gives adenocarcinoma (Barrett-related).  Gastroesophageal junction: The GE junction is the adenocarcinoma/Barrett zone.  Gastric antrum: The gastric antrum is stomach, not esophagus.  Duodenal bulb: The duodenal bulb is small bowel, not esophagus.", "basic"], ["Progressive dysphagia to SOLIDS ONLY most suggests a:", ["Fixed structural narrowing", "Primary esophageal motility disorder", "Functional swallowing complaint", "Diffuse esophageal spasm", "Globus sensation from anxiety"], 0, "Solids-only dysphagia points to a structural narrowing (cancer, EoE, Schatzki ring); dysphagia to BOTH solids and liquids points to a motility disorder — get a barium study first there.\n\nWhy not — Primary esophageal motility disorder: Motility disorders cause solid AND liquid dysphagia.  Functional swallowing complaint: Functional complaints don't progress with a fixed pattern.  Diffuse esophageal spasm: Spasm causes intermittent solid-and-liquid dysphagia.  Globus sensation from anxiety: Globus is a constant lump sensation, not progressive solid dysphagia.", "basic"], ["Concentric esophageal rings (a 'corrugated' esophagus) with recurrent food impaction in an atopic patient indicate:", ["Eosinophilic esophagitis", "A Schatzki ring", "Esophageal adenocarcinoma", "Achalasia of the sphincter", "A peptic reflux stricture"], 0, "Eosinophilic esophagitis is an allergic esophagus producing multiple concentric rings and frequent food impaction in atopic patients; a Schatzki ring is a single distal ring.\n\nWhy not — A Schatzki ring: A Schatzki ring is a SINGLE distal ring, not multiple rings.  Esophageal adenocarcinoma: Adenocarcinoma is a mass/stricture, not concentric rings in a young atopic.  Achalasia of the sphincter: Achalasia has near-normal endoscopy, not rings.  A peptic reflux stricture: A peptic stricture is a single tight narrowing, not corrugated rings.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe the use of lower endoscopic procedures for the differential diagnosis of the colorectal area", [["The most common cause of acute, painless, hemodynamically significant hematochezia in an elderly patient is:", ["Diverticulosis", "Diverticulitis", "Internal hemorrhoids", "Ischemic colitis", "Colorectal carcinoma"], 0, "Diverticulosis is the classic cause of acute, painless, large-volume lower-GI bleeding over age 50; it stops on its own in roughly 80%.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulitis: DiverticulITIS causes pain and fever, typically WITHOUT significant bleeding.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids cause small-volume bright-red bleeding.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is painful with bloody diarrhea, not painless.  Colorectal carcinoma: Colorectal cancer usually bleeds slowly/occultly, not acutely and massively.", "advanced"], ["A patient with left-lower-quadrant pain and fever but no bleeding most likely has:", ["Diverticulitis", "Diverticulosis", "Angiodysplasia", "Internal hemorrhoids", "A colonic adenoma"], 0, "DiverticulITIS = inflammation: LLQ pain and fever, usually WITHOUT significant bleeding (and colonoscopy is contraindicated acutely). DiverticulOSIS is the painless bleeder. Never mix osis and itis.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulosis: DiverticulOSIS is the painless bleeder, not the painful febrile picture.  Angiodysplasia: Angiodysplasia bleeds painlessly; it doesn't cause fever.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids cause painless bright-red bleeding, not fever.  A colonic adenoma: An adenoma is usually asymptomatic.", "advanced"], ["Discontinuous skip lesions with cobblestoning on colonoscopy indicate:", ["Crohn disease", "Ulcerative colitis", "Ischemic colitis", "Pseudomembranous colitis", "Diverticular colitis"], 0, "Crohn disease is discontinuous (skip lesions) with cobblestoning and aphthous ulcers; the diagnosis is more visual than histologic. UC is continuous from the rectum.\n\nWhy not — Ulcerative colitis: Ulcerative colitis is CONTINUOUS from the rectum, without skip lesions.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is segmental at watershed zones, not cobblestoned.  Pseudomembranous colitis: Pseudomembranous colitis shows yellow plaques (C. difficile).  Diverticular colitis: 'Diverticular colitis' is not the cobblestoning/skip pattern.", "basic"]]], [5, "Understand the indications and complications of endoscopy", [["The most dreaded complication of ERCP is:", ["Post-ERCP pancreatitis", "Esophageal perforation", "Aspiration pneumonia", "Splenic laceration", "Colonic perforation"], 0, "Manipulating the ampulla where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet can inflame the pancreas; post-ERCP pancreatitis is the dreaded complication, with an overall ~10% complication rate.\n\nWhy not — Esophageal perforation: Perforation is possible but not THE dreaded complication.  Aspiration pneumonia: Aspiration is a general anesthesia risk, not the signature ERCP complication.  Splenic laceration: Splenic injury is a colonoscopy-related rarity, not ERCP.  Colonic perforation: Colonic perforation is a colonoscopy complication, not ERCP.", "basic"]]], [6, "State the colonoscopy and the screening recommendations of the American College of Gastroenterology", [["Average-risk colorectal cancer screening should now begin at age:", ["45", "40", "50", "55", "60"], 0, "The 2022 update lowered the average-risk start age to 45 (from 50); African Americans now start at 45 as well.\n\nWhy not — 40: 40 is the high-risk/family-history start, not average-risk.  50: 50 was the OLD average-risk start, before 2022.  55: 55 is not a guideline start age.  60: 60 is far too late to begin average-risk screening.", "basic"], ["For average-risk colorectal cancer screening, the FIRST test that should be offered is:", ["Colonoscopy every 10 years", "Annual fecal immunochemical testing", "Cologuard every three years", "CT colonography every five years", "Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years"], 0, "Colonoscopy q10y should be offered FIRST; a stool test (annual FIT) is offered only to patients who decline colonoscopy — not as an equivalent menu choice.\n\nWhy not — Annual fecal immunochemical testing: Annual FIT is first-tier but offered when colonoscopy is declined, not first.  Cologuard every three years: Cologuard is second-tier and not a first offer.  CT colonography every five years: CT colonography is a second-tier option.  Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years: Flexible sigmoidoscopy is a limited second-tier option.", "basic"], ["Cologuard (FIT-DNA) is best described as a:", ["Cancer-detection test, not a prevention test", "Cancer-prevention test equal to colonoscopy", "First-tier test for high-risk patients", "Reliable test for advanced adenomas", "Replacement that needs no follow-up colonoscopy"], 0, "Cologuard is ~92% sensitive for cancer but only ~42% for advanced adenomas — so it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it (you can't remove a polyp through it). Every positive needs a colonoscopy.\n\nWhy not — Cancer-prevention test equal to colonoscopy: It is not equivalent to colonoscopy and does not prevent cancer.  First-tier test for high-risk patients: It is contraindicated in high-risk patients.  Reliable test for advanced adenomas: It misses ~58% of advanced adenomas — detection of polyps is only fair.  Replacement that needs no follow-up colonoscopy: Every positive Cologuard requires a follow-up colonoscopy.", "basic"], ["A 30-year-old's father had colon cancer at age 55. When and how often should screening colonoscopy be done?", ["Start at 40, every 5 years", "Start at 45, every 10 years", "Start at 50, every 10 years", "Start at 55, every 5 years", "Start at 45, every 5 years"], 0, "A first-degree relative with CRC under 60 makes this high-risk: colonoscopy every 5 years, starting at age 40 OR 10 years before the youngest affected relative (55 - 10 = 45), whichever is earlier — so 40.\n\nWhy not — Start at 45, every 10 years: q10y average-risk timing ignores the high-risk family history.  Start at 50, every 10 years: Start 50/q10y is the old average-risk rule, not high-risk.  Start at 55, every 5 years: 55 is too late; high-risk starts at 40 here.  Start at 45, every 5 years: Correct interval (q5y) but the start age should be 40, not 45.", "advanced"]]]]], [35, "GI Pharmacology (Lec 35–36)", [[1, "Describe the physiology of gastric acid secretion and the cellular targets that regulate it", [["On the parietal cell, acetylcholine, gastrin, and histamine each stimulate acid secretion by binding which receptors, respectively?", ["M3 muscarinic, CCK-B gastrin, and H2 receptors", "M1 muscarinic, CCK-A gastrin, and H1 receptors", "Nicotinic, secretin, and H2 receptors", "M3 muscarinic, CCK-B gastrin, and H1 receptors", "Alpha-2 adrenergic, CCK-A, and H2 receptors"], 0, "Acetylcholine acts at M3 muscarinic receptors, gastrin at CCK-B (gastrin) receptors, and histamine at H2 receptors. All three converge on protein kinases that drive the H+/K+-ATPase, which is why each is a separate drug target.\n\nWhy not — M1 muscarinic, CCK-A gastrin, and H1 receptors: M1/CCK-A/H1 are the wrong subtypes; the parietal cell uses M3, CCK-B, and H2.  Nicotinic, secretin, and H2 receptors: ACh works through muscarinic (not nicotinic) receptors, and secretin is inhibitory, not the gastrin receptor.  M3 muscarinic, CCK-B gastrin, and H1 receptors: Histamine acts at H2, not H1 — the H1 swap is the classic distractor.  Alpha-2 adrenergic, CCK-A, and H2 receptors: Alpha-2 and CCK-A are not the parietal-cell acid-secretory receptors.", "basic"], ["Prostaglandin E2 differs from acetylcholine, histamine, and gastrin at the parietal cell in that PGE2:", ["Inhibits acid secretion and is cytoprotective", "Stimulates acid secretion through CCK-B receptors", "Activates the H+/K+-ATPase directly", "Is the final common pathway all secretagogues use", "Triggers histamine release from ECL cells"], 0, "Unlike the three secretagogues, PGE2 binds parietal-cell EP receptors to INHIBIT acid secretion while enhancing mucus, bicarbonate, and mucosal blood flow — the cytoprotective arm. This is exactly why the PGE1 analog misoprostol protects against NSAID ulcers.\n\nWhy not — Stimulates acid secretion through CCK-B receptors: Gastrin (not PGE2) uses CCK-B receptors, and PGE2 inhibits rather than stimulates.  Activates the H+/K+-ATPase directly: The H+/K+-ATPase is the pump itself; PGE2 down-regulates, it does not activate it.  Is the final common pathway all secretagogues use: The H+/K+-ATPase (the pump), not PGE2, is the final common pathway.  Triggers histamine release from ECL cells: ECL-cell histamine release is driven by gastrin/ACh, not by inhibitory PGE2.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe the agents used to treat peptic ulcers and gastric acidity and their adverse effects", [["An aluminum-hydroxide / magnesium-hydroxide antacid is formulated as a combination chiefly to:", ["Counterbalance bowel effects: aluminum constipates, magnesium loosens", "Prolong the duration of acid neutralization beyond several hours", "Prevent the rebound acid hypersecretion that aluminum alone causes", "Add antimicrobial coverage against H. pylori", "Avoid the CO2 production seen with single-agent antacids"], 0, "Aluminum salts slow motility and cause constipation; magnesium salts cause an osmotic diarrhea. Combining them lets the two opposite bowel effects counterbalance — Parmar drilled this Al-constipation / Mg-diarrhea pairing repeatedly.\n\nWhy not — Prolong the duration of acid neutralization beyond several hours: Antacids have a uniformly short duration (30-60 min); combining them does not prolong it.  Prevent the rebound acid hypersecretion that aluminum alone causes: Rebound hypersecretion is associated with calcium carbonate, and is not the reason for combining Al and Mg.  Add antimicrobial coverage against H. pylori: Bismuth (not Al/Mg) contributes antimicrobial activity in H. pylori therapy.  Avoid the CO2 production seen with single-agent antacids: CaCO3 and NaHCO3 generate CO2; the Al/Mg combination is not designed around that.", "basic"], ["Which acid-suppressive agent irreversibly inhibits the gastric H+/K+-ATPase, so that recovery of acid secretion requires new pump synthesis over roughly 18-24 hours?", ["Omeprazole", "Famotidine", "Vonoprazan", "Aluminum hydroxide", "Misoprostol"], 0, "Proton pump inhibitors such as omeprazole are prodrugs that covalently and irreversibly bind the activated H+/K+-ATPase; acid secretion only returns as new pumps are synthesized over ~18-24 hours, giving a long duration despite a short plasma half-life.\n\nWhy not — Famotidine: Famotidine is a reversible H2-receptor antagonist, not a pump inhibitor.  Vonoprazan: Vonoprazan (PCAB) blocks the pump's K+ site reversibly — it does not bind covalently.  Aluminum hydroxide: Aluminum hydroxide neutralizes acid already secreted; it does not touch the pump.  Misoprostol: Misoprostol is a PGE1 analog acting at EP receptors, not the pump.", "basic"], ["A patient on chronic high-dose cimetidine develops gynecomastia. The mechanism is:", ["Antiandrogenic activity of cimetidine", "Hyperprolactinemia from dopamine-receptor blockade", "Estrogen-receptor agonism by the imidazole ring", "Inhibition of aromatase in adipose tissue", "Suppression of luteinizing hormone secretion"], 0, "Cimetidine has antiandrogenic effects at high dose, producing gynecomastia and galactorrhea — an effect essentially unique to cimetidine among H2RAs (famotidine and others are free of it).\n\nWhy not — Hyperprolactinemia from dopamine-receptor blockade: Dopamine-blockade hyperprolactinemia is the metoclopramide mechanism (Lec 36), not cimetidine's.  Estrogen-receptor agonism by the imidazole ring: Cimetidine antagonizes androgen action; it is not an estrogen-receptor agonist.  Inhibition of aromatase in adipose tissue: Aromatase inhibition would lower estrogen and is not how cimetidine acts.  Suppression of luteinizing hormone secretion: Cimetidine does not work by suppressing LH.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Compare the relationship of histamine-2 receptor antagonists to proton pump inhibitors and the effect of acid suppression on vitamin B12 and intrinsic factor", [["Compared with an H2-receptor antagonist, a proton pump inhibitor provides acid suppression that is best described as:", ["Greater and longer-lasting because pump inhibition is irreversible", "Roughly equal in magnitude but with a faster onset of action", "Weaker but free of any tachyphylaxis", "Greater only against nocturnal, not meal-stimulated, acid", "Greater but reversible, so acid returns within one drug half-life"], 0, "PPIs suppress >90% of basal and stimulated acid versus the ~60-70% achieved by H2RAs, and because PPIs bind the pump irreversibly the effect outlasts the drug. H2RAs are reversible, weaker, and develop tachyphylaxis over days to weeks.\n\nWhy not — Roughly equal in magnitude but with a faster onset of action: PPIs are substantially MORE potent than H2RAs, and H2RAs actually have the faster onset.  Weaker but free of any tachyphylaxis: PPIs are stronger, and it is the H2RAs (not PPIs) that show tachyphylaxis.  Greater only against nocturnal, not meal-stimulated, acid: The nocturnal-selectivity description fits H2RAs; PPIs suppress both basal and stimulated acid.  Greater but reversible, so acid returns within one drug half-life: PPI suppression is irreversible and outlasts the plasma half-life — acid does not return that quickly.", "basic"], ["Long-term acid suppression with a PPI predisposes to deficiency of which vitamin, because gastric acid is needed to release it from dietary protein?", ["Vitamin B12, cobalamin", "Vitamin C, ascorbate", "Folate", "Vitamin K", "Thiamine, vitamin B1"], 0, "Chronic acid suppression decreases the bioavailability of vitamin B12, because acid is required to cleave cobalamin from dietary protein before intrinsic factor can bind it. Both PPIs (slide 17) and long-term H2RA use are implicated.\n\nWhy not — Vitamin C, ascorbate: Vitamin C absorption is not acid-dependent in this way.  Folate: Folate is absorbed in the jejunum and is not the acid-suppression deficiency.  Vitamin K: Vitamin K depends on bile and gut flora, not gastric acid.  Thiamine, vitamin B1: Thiamine is not the vitamin affected by chronic acid suppression.", "basic"]]], [4, "Describe the clinically significant drug interactions of acid-suppressive and mucosal-protective agents", [["A patient who had a coronary stent placed and takes clopidogrel needs a PPI. Which agent is the safest choice, and why?", ["Pantoprazole, because omeprazole/esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19 and reduce clopidogrel activation", "Omeprazole, because it has the least effect on CYP2C19", "Esomeprazole, because the S-isomer bypasses CYP2C19", "Any PPI, because clopidogrel is not metabolized by CYP enzymes", "Famotidine is mandatory, because all PPIs are absolutely contraindicated"], 0, "Clopidogrel is a prodrug activated by CYP2C19. Omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19, blunting clopidogrel's antiplatelet effect, so they are avoided; pantoprazole has minimal CYP2C19 inhibition and is the preferred PPI in this setting.\n\nWhy not — Omeprazole, because it has the least effect on CYP2C19: Omeprazole is one of the worst offenders — it strongly inhibits CYP2C19.  Esomeprazole, because the S-isomer bypasses CYP2C19: Esomeprazole is the S-isomer of omeprazole and shares the CYP2C19 inhibition.  Any PPI, because clopidogrel is not metabolized by CYP enzymes: Clopidogrel is a prodrug that absolutely requires CYP2C19 for activation.  Famotidine is mandatory, because all PPIs are absolutely contraindicated: PPIs are not absolutely contraindicated; a low-interaction PPI (pantoprazole) is acceptable.", "advanced"], ["Sucralfate should NOT be co-administered with a PPI or antacid primarily because:", ["Sucralfate needs an acidic pH to form its gel", "The combination causes dangerous aluminum toxicity in normal kidneys", "PPIs accelerate sucralfate's hepatic first-pass metabolism", "Sucralfate inactivates PPIs in the small intestine", "Both bind the H+/K+-ATPase and compete for the pump"], 0, "Sucralfate is a sucrose-sulfate / aluminum-hydroxide complex that needs an acidic environment to polymerize into the viscous gel that binds the ulcer base. Raising gastric pH with a PPI, H2RA, or antacid removes the activation step, so the agents are spaced apart or not combined. (Sucralfate also impairs quinolone absorption.)\n\nWhy not — The combination causes dangerous aluminum toxicity in normal kidneys: Aluminum accumulation is a concern mainly in renal impairment, and is not the reason for the timing rule.  PPIs accelerate sucralfate's hepatic first-pass metabolism: Sucralfate is barely absorbed; this is not a hepatic-metabolism interaction.  Sucralfate inactivates PPIs in the small intestine: The problem is loss of sucralfate's own acid activation, not inactivation of the PPI.  Both bind the H+/K+-ATPase and compete for the pump: Sucralfate does not act at the proton pump at all.", "basic"]]], [5, "Describe the regimens used for Helicobacter pylori eradication", [["A 55-year-old with a duodenal ulcer tests positive for H. pylori on stool antigen. He has no penicillin allergy and lives in a region of high clarithromycin resistance. The preferred first-line regimen and the required follow-up are:", ["14-day bismuth quadruple therapy, then mandatory confirmation of eradication", "Clarithromycin-based triple therapy for 7 days, with no eradication testing needed", "A PPI alone for 8 weeks, then repeat endoscopy", "Single-dose azithromycin plus an antacid, then symptom monitoring only", "Sucralfate plus misoprostol for 14 days, then a urea breath test"], 0, "The gold-standard first-line regimen is 14-day Optimized bismuth quadruple therapy — PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth — which avoids clarithromycin where resistance is high. Under the 2024 guidelines, confirmation of eradication (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) is now mandatory for every treated patient.\n\nWhy not — Clarithromycin-based triple therapy for 7 days, with no eradication testing needed: Clarithromycin was dropped from first-line use for resistance, and eradication testing is now mandatory — both halves are wrong.  A PPI alone for 8 weeks, then repeat endoscopy: Acid suppression alone does not eradicate the organism; antibiotics are required.  Single-dose azithromycin plus an antacid, then symptom monitoring only: A single antibiotic with an antacid is not an evidence-based eradication regimen.  Sucralfate plus misoprostol for 14 days, then a urea breath test: Sucralfate and misoprostol are mucosal agents with no antimicrobial role against H. pylori.", "advanced"]]], [6, "List the categories of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["A patient prone to motion sickness needs a prophylactic patch placed behind the ear. The drug acts as a:", ["Muscarinic M1 receptor antagonist", "Histamine H1 receptor antagonist", "Dopamine D2 receptor antagonist", "Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonist", "Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonist"], 0, "The behind-the-ear motion-sickness patch is scopolamine, an M1 muscarinic antagonist that crosses the blood-brain barrier to act centrally at the area postrema and on the vestibular system. H1 antihistamines (meclizine, dimenhydrinate) also treat motion sickness but are oral, not the patch.\n\nWhy not — Histamine H1 receptor antagonist: H1 antihistamines (meclizine, dimenhydrinate) treat motion sickness too, but are not the scopolamine patch.  Dopamine D2 receptor antagonist: D2 antagonists treat CINV/PONV and are ineffective for motion sickness.  Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonist: 5-HT3 antagonists are for CINV/PONV/RINV and are explicitly ineffective for motion sickness.  Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonist: NK1 antagonists target the delayed phase of CINV, not motion sickness.", "advanced"], ["Which agent belongs to the serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonist class of antiemetics?", ["Palonosetron", "Prochlorperazine", "Aprepitant", "Scopolamine", "Dronabinol"], 0, "The 5-HT3 antagonists are the '-setrons': ondansetron, dolasetron, granisetron, and palonosetron. The drug-ending shortcut (-setron = serotonin) is the fastest way to bin these agents by class.\n\nWhy not — Prochlorperazine: Prochlorperazine is a phenothiazine D2 antagonist.  Aprepitant: Aprepitant is an NK1 antagonist (a '-pitant').  Scopolamine: Scopolamine is an M1 muscarinic antagonist.  Dronabinol: Dronabinol is a cannabinoid CB1 agonist.", "basic"]]], [7, "Discuss the mechanism of action of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["A chemotherapy patient develops nausea on days 2-4 after the infusion. The mediator and target driving this delayed phase are:", ["Substance P acting at NK1 receptors", "Serotonin acting at 5-HT3 receptors", "Dopamine acting at D2 receptors", "Histamine acting at H1 receptors", "Acetylcholine acting at M1 receptors"], 0, "The delayed phase of CINV (roughly days 1-5) is mediated centrally by substance P binding NK1 receptors — which is why NK1 antagonists (-pitants) are added for delayed coverage. The acute phase (<24 h) is the serotonin/5-HT3 peripheral pathway, the classic distractor here.\n\nWhy not — Serotonin acting at 5-HT3 receptors: Serotonin/5-HT3 drives the ACUTE phase (<24 h), not the delayed phase.  Dopamine acting at D2 receptors: D2 is the CTZ target for several antiemetics but is not the delayed-phase mediator.  Histamine acting at H1 receptors: H1 mediates vestibular/motion nausea, not delayed-phase CINV.  Acetylcholine acting at M1 receptors: M1 mediates motion sickness via the vestibular system, not delayed-phase CINV.", "advanced"], ["Ondansetron exerts its antiemetic effect by blocking 5-HT3 receptors at which two sites?", ["Central area postrema and peripheral vagal afferents", "Vestibular nuclei and the cerebral cortex", "Lower esophageal sphincter and gastric antrum", "Nigrostriatal pathway and the basal ganglia", "Carotid body and the respiratory center"], 0, "5-HT3 antagonists work at two sites: centrally in the CNS at the area postrema/CTZ and peripherally on GI vagal afferent nerve terminals — giving both central and peripheral antiemetic effect. This dual location is why they cover CINV, PONV, and RINV.\n\nWhy not — Vestibular nuclei and the cerebral cortex: Vestibular/cortical sites are H1/M1 territory (motion sickness), not 5-HT3.  Lower esophageal sphincter and gastric antrum: LES and antrum are prokinetic (metoclopramide) targets, not 5-HT3 antiemetic sites.  Nigrostriatal pathway and the basal ganglia: Nigrostriatal D2 blockade explains EPS from dopamine antagonists, not setron action.  Carotid body and the respiratory center: The carotid body and respiratory center are not 5-HT3 antiemetic sites.", "basic"], ["Metoclopramide relieves diabetic gastroparesis because, beyond blocking central D2 receptors, it also:", ["Facilitates gut cholinergic transmission, raising LES tone and emptying", "Directly stimulates motilin receptors on GI smooth muscle", "Agonizes 5-HT4 receptors to trigger the peristaltic reflex", "Inhibits acetylcholinesterase to raise gut acetylcholine levels", "Blocks peripheral 5-HT3 receptors on vagal afferent fibers"], 0, "Metoclopramide is the dual-action drug: central D2 antagonism at the CTZ gives the antiemetic effect, while peripherally it facilitates cholinergic (ACh) transmission in the gut — increasing LES tone, speeding gastric emptying, and promoting small-bowel transit. Each distractor is the mechanism of a DIFFERENT prokinetic.\n\nWhy not — Directly stimulates motilin receptors on GI smooth muscle: Direct motilin-receptor agonism is erythromycin's mechanism.  Agonizes 5-HT4 receptors to trigger the peristaltic reflex: 5-HT4 agonism is prucalopride's mechanism.  Inhibits acetylcholinesterase to raise gut acetylcholine levels: AChE inhibition is neostigmine's mechanism (colonic pseudo-obstruction).  Blocks peripheral 5-HT3 receptors on vagal afferent fibers: Blocking peripheral 5-HT3 is the setron antiemetic mechanism, not metoclopramide's prokinetic action.", "basic"]]], [8, "Discuss the therapeutic and adverse effects of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["Before continuing metoclopramide in a patient on a multi-month course, the key adverse effect to monitor for and time-limit therapy against is:", ["Tardive dyskinesia, potentially irreversible", "Profound apomorphine-induced hypotension", "Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome", "Serotonin syndrome from 5-HT3 blockade", "Hyperglycemia and weight gain"], 0, "Metoclopramide carries a boxed warning for tardive dyskinesia, which can be irreversible; risk rises with treatment duration and cumulative dose, so use is limited to no more than 12 weeks whenever possible. Parmar flags this as the exam-relevant adverse effect for this widely used drug.\n\nWhy not — Profound apomorphine-induced hypotension: Apomorphine hypotension is the ondansetron contraindication, not a metoclopramide effect.  Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome: CHS is a chronic cannabinoid (dronabinol/nabilone) effect.  Serotonin syndrome from 5-HT3 blockade: Serotonin syndrome is a rare setron effect, not the metoclopramide boxed warning.  Hyperglycemia and weight gain: Hyperglycemia/weight gain are dexamethasone effects, not metoclopramide's.", "advanced"], ["Droperidol carries a boxed warning that mandates a 12-lead ECG before dosing and continued monitoring afterward because it causes:", ["QT prolongation and torsades", "Irreversible tardive dyskinesia", "Profound serotonin syndrome", "Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome", "Acute dystonic respiratory depression"], 0, "Droperidol (a butyrophenone D2 antagonist used for PONV) has a boxed warning for QT prolongation and torsades de pointes; it is contraindicated with a prolonged baseline QT, and all patients need a 12-lead ECG before and for 2-3 hours after the dose.\n\nWhy not — Irreversible tardive dyskinesia: Irreversible TD is metoclopramide's boxed warning, not droperidol's ECG concern.  Profound serotonin syndrome: Serotonin syndrome is a setron risk, not droperidol's.  Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome: CHS is a cannabinoid effect.  Acute dystonic respiratory depression: Respiratory depression is the promethazine/dimenhydrinate pediatric warning, not droperidol's QT issue.", "basic"], ["Compared with first-generation setrons, palonosetron is preferred for both acute and delayed CINV chiefly because it has:", ["Higher receptor affinity and a longer half-life", "Selective antagonism at NK1 substance-P receptors", "Added muscarinic and histaminic blockade", "Direct dopamine D2 antagonism in the CTZ", "A faster onset with a shorter duration of action"], 0, "Palonosetron is the second-generation 5-HT3 antagonist: higher receptor affinity and a markedly longer half-life give it efficacy against both acute and delayed CINV and the least QT effect of the class. It does not gain its advantage by acting on other receptors.\n\nWhy not — Selective antagonism at NK1 substance-P receptors: NK1 antagonism is the -pitants; setrons are selective for 5-HT3.  Added muscarinic and histaminic blockade: Multi-receptor (M/H) blockade describes olanzapine, not palonosetron.  Direct dopamine D2 antagonism in the CTZ: Setrons lack significant D2 activity by design.  A faster onset with a shorter duration of action: Palonosetron has a LONGER, not shorter, duration.", "basic"]]], [9, "Discuss the potential contraindications and drug interactions of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["A patient with Parkinson's disease needs an antiemetic. Which class must be avoided because it worsens the underlying disease?", ["Dopamine D2 receptor antagonists", "Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonists", "Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonists targeting substance P", "Histamine H1 receptor antagonists", "Cannabinoid CB1 receptor agonists"], 0, "Parkinson's reflects dopamine-neuron loss, so blocking dopamine worsens it — every D2 antagonist antiemetic (prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, amisulpride) is contraindicated. This is the same D2-blockade mechanism behind their EPS.\n\nWhy not — Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonists: 5-HT3 antagonists don't block dopamine and are not Parkinson's-contraindicated.  Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonists targeting substance P: NK1 antagonists target substance P, not dopamine.  Histamine H1 receptor antagonists: H1 antihistamines are not contraindicated by dopamine blockade.  Cannabinoid CB1 receptor agonists: Cannabinoids act at CB1 and don't worsen Parkinson's by this mechanism.", "advanced"], ["A highly emetogenic regimen is covered with a 5-HT3 antagonist, dexamethasone, and an NK1 antagonist. If aprepitant is the NK1 agent, the prescriber must adjust therapy by:", ["Reducing the dexamethasone dose, because aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4", "Leaving dexamethasone unchanged, because aprepitant induces CYP3A4", "Reducing the dexamethasone dose, because aprepitant inhibits CYP2D6", "Doubling the dexamethasone dose to overcome CYP3A4 induction", "Switching dexamethasone to the 5-HT3 antagonist to avoid the interaction"], 0, "Aprepitant (and fosaprepitant/netupitant) are moderate CYP3A4 inhibitors. Dexamethasone is a CYP3A4 substrate, so inhibiting that enzyme raises dexamethasone levels and risks toxicity — the dexamethasone dose must be reduced. Rolapitant would be the contrast: it inhibits CYP2D6, not CYP3A4, so it needs no adjustment. Parmar flags this as a frequent COMLEX P450 question.\n\nWhy not — Leaving dexamethasone unchanged, because aprepitant induces CYP3A4: Aprepitant inhibits (does not induce) CYP3A4, so dexamethasone is NOT left unchanged.  Reducing the dexamethasone dose, because aprepitant inhibits CYP2D6: Aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4, not CYP2D6 — that's rolapitant (which needs no adjustment).  Doubling the dexamethasone dose to overcome CYP3A4 induction: Inhibition raises levels, so the dose is reduced, not doubled.  Switching dexamethasone to the 5-HT3 antagonist to avoid the interaction: You reduce the dexamethasone dose; you don't substitute the setron for it.", "advanced"]]]]], [37, "Abdominal Trauma (Lec 37)", [[1, "Describe abdominal anatomy and mapping", [["A stab wound to the left upper quadrant is most likely to injure which organ?", ["Spleen", "Appendix", "Sigmoid colon", "Gallbladder", "Cecum"], 0, "The left upper quadrant houses the spleen (plus the left lobe of liver, stomach, body of pancreas, and left kidney). The spleen's thin capsule and ligamentous attachments make it the classic LUQ injury.\n\nWhy not — Appendix: The appendix is a right-lower-quadrant structure, not LUQ.  Sigmoid colon: The sigmoid colon is a left-lower-quadrant structure.  Gallbladder: The gallbladder is in the right upper quadrant and rarely injured.  Cecum: The cecum is in the right lower quadrant.", "advanced"], ["Which structure is retroperitoneal and therefore vulnerable to a crush injury against the spine?", ["Pancreas", "Transverse colon", "Stomach", "Small intestine", "Gallbladder"], 0, "The pancreas lies retroperitoneally across the spine, so a midline compressive force can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column. Mobile organs like the small intestine slide out of the way.\n\nWhy not — Transverse colon: The transverse colon is intraperitoneal and relatively mobile.  Stomach: The stomach is intraperitoneal and gets injured mainly when markedly distended.  Small intestine: The small intestine is mobile and usually slips away from blunt force.  Gallbladder: The gallbladder is intraperitoneal and very rarely ruptures.", "basic"], ["The abdominal aorta bifurcates into the common iliac arteries at approximately which level?", ["Fourth-to-fifth lumbar vertebra", "First lumbar vertebra", "Twelfth thoracic vertebra", "First sacral vertebra", "Tenth thoracic vertebra"], 0, "The abdominal aorta begins below the diaphragm and bifurcates into the right and left common iliac arteries at about the L4–L5 level — anatomy that matters for where a REBOA balloon can be safely seated.\n\nWhy not — First lumbar vertebra: L1 is roughly where the aorta gives off the renal/SMA region, not where it bifurcates.  Twelfth thoracic vertebra: T12 is near the aortic hiatus where the aorta enters the abdomen.  First sacral vertebra: S1 is below the bifurcation, in the iliac territory.  Tenth thoracic vertebra: T10 is the esophageal-hiatus level, well above the abdominal aorta.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe diagnostic imaging and lab studies requested for abdominal trauma patients", [["During a FAST examination in a trauma patient, the sonographer is primarily looking for:", ["Free intraperitoneal blood", "Gallstones in the gallbladder", "Bowel-wall thickening", "Renal artery stenosis", "An abdominal aortic aneurysm"], 0, "FAST (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) screens the dependent spaces for free fluid — blood — and can also reveal air and gross organ injury. Density even lets you tell blood from serous fluid. Rose's single biggest point was to learn ultrasound.\n\nWhy not — Gallstones in the gallbladder: Gallstones are a non-trauma indication; FAST is hunting for free fluid.  Bowel-wall thickening: Bowel-wall thickening is an inflammatory finding, not the FAST target.  Renal artery stenosis: Renal artery stenosis is a chronic vascular question, not a trauma FAST.  An abdominal aortic aneurysm: An AAA can be seen on ultrasound but is not what the trauma FAST is for.", "advanced"], ["A trauma patient is hypotensive and tachycardic with a tense, distended abdomen and a positive FAST. The next step is:", ["Immediate exploratory laparotomy", "CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with contrast", "Admit for serial abdominal exams", "Diagnostic peritoneal lavage", "MRI of the abdomen"], 0, "An unstable patient with a positive FAST is exsanguinating into the abdomen and goes straight to the OR — there is no time to scan. CT is reserved for the patient you can stabilize. Stability, not the organ, drives the disposition.\n\nWhy not — CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with contrast: CT is only for the patient who stabilizes; an unstable patient cannot wait for it.  Admit for serial abdominal exams: Serial exams are for a stable, reassuring patient, not a crashing one.  Diagnostic peritoneal lavage: DPL is largely historical and would only confirm what the positive FAST already shows.  MRI of the abdomen: MRI takes far too long for an unstable trauma patient.", "advanced"], ["A hemodynamically stable blunt-trauma patient has a white-count differential showing a left shift with rising leukocytes. This finding most directly suggests:", ["An evolving infectious/inflammatory process from visceral contamination", "Acute blood loss with hemodilution", "A normal stress response requiring no action", "An electrolyte disturbance on the metabolic panel", "Renal injury reaching the collecting system"], 0, "A left shift with increasing leukocytes signals the body mobilizing white cells against contamination — for example a perforated viscus spilling bowel content. The H/H tracks blood loss; the WBC differential tracks contamination/infection.\n\nWhy not — Acute blood loss with hemodilution: Blood loss is read from the hemoglobin/hematocrit, not the WBC left shift.  A normal stress response requiring no action: A frank left shift with rising leukocytes is not a finding to ignore.  An electrolyte disturbance on the metabolic panel: Electrolyte disturbances show on the BMP, not as a WBC left shift.  Renal injury reaching the collecting system: Collecting-system injury is signaled by hematuria, not the WBC differential.", "advanced"]]], [3, "List different types of abdominal trauma", [["A surgeon tears the splenic capsule while retracting on the gastrosplenic ligament during a hiatal hernia repair. This is an example of which type of trauma?", ["Iatrogenic", "Blast", "Crush", "Penetrating", "Deceleration"], 0, "Injury caused by the medical procedure itself is iatrogenic. Rose noted the spleen is injured in roughly 2% of left-upper-quadrant operations via traction on the gastrosplenic ligament — a traction-type capsular avulsion.\n\nWhy not — Blast: Blast injury is from an explosive pressure wave, not an operation.  Crush: Crush is external compression, e.g., against the spine.  Penetrating: Penetrating implies an object breaching the wall, not surgical traction.  Deceleration: Deceleration is the rapid-stop mechanism of MVAs, not operative traction.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe splenic, liver, and renal injuries", [["The most frequently injured solid organ in blunt abdominal trauma is the:", ["Spleen", "Liver", "Kidney", "Pancreas", "Stomach"], 0, "The spleen is the most frequently injured organ following blunt trauma to the abdomen or lower thorax, and splenic injury is the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its thin capsule tears easily.\n\nWhy not — Liver: The liver is also commonly injured but is not the single most frequent in blunt trauma.  Kidney: The kidney is injured less often and usually with flank/back force.  Pancreas: The pancreas is injured mainly by focal crush against the spine, not commonly.  Stomach: The stomach is rarely injured unless markedly distended.", "advanced"], ["A patient with a splenic injury complains of left-shoulder pain and hiccups. This finding is:", ["Kehr's sign", "Ballance's sign", "Cullen sign", "Gray-Turner sign", "Cullen-Murphy sign"], 0, "Kehr's sign is left-shoulder pain referred from diaphragmatic irritation by subdiaphragmatic blood — the same phrenic-nerve irritation that causes the hiccups. Rose flagged it explicitly as a board question.\n\nWhy not — Ballance's sign: Ballance's sign is fixed dullness to percussion (a mass effect), and is seldom seen.  Cullen sign: Cullen sign is periumbilical ecchymosis, not referred shoulder pain.  Gray-Turner sign: Gray-Turner sign is flank ecchymosis, not referred shoulder pain.  Cullen-Murphy sign: There is no such entity; this distractor mixes two unrelated eponyms.", "advanced"], ["A shattered spleen with multiple fractures and hilar injury is best classified as:", ["Grade IV–V (not repairable)", "Grade I (minor capsular tear)", "Grade II (capsular avulsion, minor)", "Grade III (through-and-through laceration)", "Grade 0 (contusion only)"], 0, "Grades IV–V are severe stellate fractures, crush/bisection, hilar injury, and the shattered spleen — injuries that are not repairable and require splenectomy. Grades I–III can usually be repaired or observed.\n\nWhy not — Grade I (minor capsular tear): Grade I is a minor capsular tear or laceration, easily repaired.  Grade II (capsular avulsion, minor): Grade II adds a capsular avulsion but most of the spleen is intact.  Grade III (through-and-through laceration): Grade III is a major fracture/through-and-through laceration — still often repairable.  Grade 0 (contusion only): AAST splenic grading runs I–V; there is no 'grade 0 contusion' category here.", "advanced"], ["Why are children with splenic injury preferentially managed with repair or observation rather than splenectomy?", ["To prevent overwhelming infection after splenectomy", "Because their spleens cannot be removed surgically", "Because pediatric spleens never rupture", "To preserve red-cell production by the spleen", "Because antibiotics fully replace splenic function"], 0, "Splenectomy removes the filter for encapsulated bacteria and lowers IgM and opsonin production, leaving the patient — especially a child — at risk for overwhelming post-splenectomy infection. So we save the spleen when it is safe.\n\nWhy not — Because their spleens cannot be removed surgically: Pediatric spleens can be removed; we avoid it to preserve immune function.  Because pediatric spleens never rupture: Children's spleens absolutely can rupture — that is the whole problem.  To preserve red-cell production by the spleen: The spleen's key lost function here is immune filtering/opsonization, not adult RBC production.  Because antibiotics fully replace splenic function: Vaccination and prophylaxis help but do not fully replace splenic function.", "advanced"], ["A patient had a resolving splenic hematoma observed in hospital, then returns two weeks later in shock with a growing hematoma. This is best described as:", ["Delayed splenic rupture", "Spontaneous splenic rupture", "A grade I capsular tear", "Subphrenic abscess", "Iatrogenic splenic injury"], 0, "Delayed splenic rupture presents with instability days to weeks (usually within 2 weeks) after trauma, from a slowly enlarging subcapsular hematoma that finally bursts — Rose's own observed case. It is distinct from spontaneous rupture of a diseased spleen.\n\nWhy not — Spontaneous splenic rupture: Spontaneous rupture occurs in a diseased spleen (malaria, mono) without antecedent trauma.  A grade I capsular tear: A grade I capsular tear is a minor injury, not a delayed catastrophic rupture.  Subphrenic abscess: A subphrenic abscess is a post-splenectomy infection, not a hematoma rupture.  Iatrogenic splenic injury: Iatrogenic injury happens during an operation, not two weeks later at home.", "advanced"], ["Worldwide, the most common cause of spontaneous rupture of a diseased spleen is:", ["Malaria", "Infectious mononucleosis", "Polycythemia vera", "Chronic leukemia", "Sarcoidosis"], 0, "Worldwide the leading cause of spontaneous splenic rupture is malaria, followed by infectious mononucleosis. Both engorge and enlarge the spleen, stretching its thin capsule until it tears.\n\nWhy not — Infectious mononucleosis: Infectious mononucleosis is the second-most-common cause (and the classic U.S. one).  Polycythemia vera: Polycythemia vera enlarges the spleen but is not the leading worldwide cause.  Chronic leukemia: Chronic leukemia causes splenomegaly but is not the top cause worldwide.  Sarcoidosis: Sarcoidosis is on the list but is uncommon as a rupture cause.", "basic"], ["In a stable patient with blunt renal trauma, gross hematuria indicates that the injury has reached the:", ["Renal collecting system", "Renal capsule only", "Perirenal fat without parenchyma", "Adrenal gland", "Ureterovesical junction"], 0, "Hematuria means the laceration has communicated with the collecting system (renal pelvis). A contusion or contained subcapsular hematoma that spares the collecting system may show little or no blood. The depth of laceration drives the need for surgery.\n\nWhy not — Renal capsule only: A capsule-only injury (grade I) gives at most microscopic hematuria.  Perirenal fat without parenchyma: Injury limited to perirenal fat does not produce gross hematuria.  Adrenal gland: Adrenal injury does not produce hematuria.  Ureterovesical junction: The UVJ is distal; renal-pelvis communication is what gross hematuria signals here.", "advanced"], ["A child with a rapid-deceleration injury has flank pain but a NEGATIVE urinalysis. The injury you must not miss is:", ["Avulsion of the ureteropelvic junction", "A grade I renal contusion", "A bladder rupture", "A renal-vein thrombosis with hematuria", "A simple renal capsular tear"], 0, "In children, rapid deceleration can avulse the ureteropelvic junction; because no urine then reaches the bladder, the urinalysis can be falsely negative. A negative UA does not exclude a major renal injury in this setting — image the child.\n\nWhy not — A grade I renal contusion: A grade I contusion would typically still show some hematuria, not justify the concern.  A bladder rupture: Bladder rupture usually shows hematuria and a different mechanism.  A renal-vein thrombosis with hematuria: Vein thrombosis would not be the classic 'negative UA' pediatric trap — UPJ avulsion is.  A simple renal capsular tear: A simple capsular tear is minor and is not the dangerous miss here.", "advanced"], ["A stable patient with blunt flank trauma has CT showing a renal laceration. The single factor that most determines whether operative exploration is needed is:", ["The depth of the laceration", "The patient's age", "The presence of microscopic hematuria", "Whether a rib is fractured", "The serum creatinine on admission"], 0, "Rose's rule: it is the depth of the laceration that determines the need for surgery. A stable patient with a deep injury into the collecting system or vasculature may need exploration, while shallow injuries trend toward observation; an unstable patient goes to the OR regardless.\n\nWhy not — The patient's age: Age affects overall risk tolerance but does not define the renal-surgery decision.  The presence of microscopic hematuria: Microscopic hematuria alone often does not even mandate imaging in stable adults.  Whether a rib is fractured: A rib fracture is an associated finding, not the determinant of renal surgery.  The serum creatinine on admission: Creatinine reflects baseline function, not the acute need to explore.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Describe pancreatic, pelvic, and thoracoabdominal trauma", [["Pancreatic injury from blunt trauma most characteristically results from:", ["A crush against the spine", "A penetrating flank stab wound", "Rapid deceleration tearing a ligament", "An iatrogenic traction injury", "A blast pressure wave"], 0, "The pancreas lies across the spine retroperitoneally, so a focal midline blow (steering wheel, handlebar) crushes — or even transects — it against the vertebral column. Rose's garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine.\n\nWhy not — A penetrating flank stab wound: Penetrating injury can hit the pancreas but is not the characteristic blunt mechanism.  Rapid deceleration tearing a ligament: Deceleration ligament tears are the spleen/liver story, not the pancreas.  An iatrogenic traction injury: Iatrogenic traction is the splenic-capsule mechanism, not pancreatic.  A blast pressure wave: Blast injury is a different mechanism than the classic spine-crush.", "advanced"], ["Which laboratory studies are most useful for suspected pancreatic injury?", ["Amylase and lipase", "Troponin and BNP", "PT/PTT/INR", "Lactate dehydrogenase and haptoglobin", "Ammonia and bilirubin"], 0, "Pancreatic enzymes — amylase and lipase — rise with pancreatic injury, and ERCP can define the ductal anatomy. They are also part of what is checked for in peritoneal fluid when lavage is used.\n\nWhy not — Troponin and BNP: Troponin/BNP are cardiac markers, irrelevant to pancreatic injury.  PT/PTT/INR: Coagulation studies matter before surgery but do not diagnose pancreatic injury.  Lactate dehydrogenase and haptoglobin: LDH/haptoglobin assess hemolysis, not the pancreas.  Ammonia and bilirubin: Ammonia/bilirubin reflect hepatic function, not pancreatic injury.", "basic"], ["Diagnostic peritoneal lavage (DPL) is now largely of historical interest mainly because:", ["CT answers the same questions quickly", "DPL cannot detect intraperitoneal blood", "DPL requires general anesthesia to perform", "Ultrasound cannot be used in trauma", "Amylase in lavage fluid is never informative"], 0, "DPL once answered 'is there blood, bile, fecal material, or amylase in the abdomen?' but CT answers those quickly and noninvasively, so lavage is rarely performed now (still used where imaging is unavailable).\n\nWhy not — DPL cannot detect intraperitoneal blood: DPL is in fact very sensitive for blood — that was its purpose.  DPL requires general anesthesia to perform: DPL is a bedside procedure, not one requiring general anesthesia.  Ultrasound cannot be used in trauma: Ultrasound (FAST) is heavily used in trauma — it complements CT.  Amylase in lavage fluid is never informative: Amylase in lavage fluid is informative; that was part of DPL's value.", "basic"], ["REBOA (resuscitative endovascular balloon occlusion of the aorta) is used to temporarily control hemorrhage and:", ["May be deployed only in certain zones", "Is placed across the renal arteries to maximize control", "Replaces the need for any operative repair", "Is a permanent indwelling device", "Is contraindicated in all hemorrhagic shock"], 0, "REBOA buys time by occluding the aorta in defined zones; the balloon is deliberately NOT placed across the renal-artery segment (Zone II) because that would cause renal ischemia. It is a temporizing bridge, not a definitive repair.\n\nWhy not — Is placed across the renal arteries to maximize control: Occluding across the renal arteries causes renal ischemia — that zone is avoided.  Replaces the need for any operative repair: REBOA is temporizing; definitive control still requires surgery or angioembolization.  Is a permanent indwelling device: It is a temporary balloon, not a permanent device.  Is contraindicated in all hemorrhagic shock: REBOA is used precisely in selected hemorrhagic-shock patients.", "basic"]]]]], [38, "Abdominal Pain — Diverticulitis (Lec 38)", [[1, "List the appropriate history questions needed for a patient with diverticulitis", [["A 68-year-old woman has 3 days of left-lower-quadrant abdominal pain with subjective fever. Following Moljo's approach, the FIRST framing that should drive your history is:", ["What anatomic structures sit in that quadrant", "Which antibiotic regimen she will ultimately need", "Her modified Hinchey stage", "Whether she requires emergency surgery", "Which CT contrast medium is safest"], 0, "Moljo's repeated lesson is anatomy-first: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Naming what sits in the painful quadrant (colon, ovary, bladder) generates the differential, and the targeted history questions follow from it. Staging, antibiotics, and contrast come later.\n\nWhy not — Which antibiotic regimen she will ultimately need: The regimen is a management decision made after diagnosis, not the opening history framing.  Her modified Hinchey stage: Hinchey is a CT-based stage assigned after imaging, not a history starting point.  Whether she requires emergency surgery: Surgical need is decided by stability and stage, not at the history-taking step.  Which CT contrast medium is safest: Contrast choice is a testing decision, not the frame that drives the history.", "advanced"], ["A man with known diverticular disease reports passing air in his urine (pneumaturia) and seeing stool in the urine. These history clues point to:", ["A colovesical fistula", "An uncomplicated diverticular abscess", "A simple urinary tract infection", "A free perforation with peritonitis", "Diverticular bleeding"], 0, "Pneumaturia (air in urine) and fecaluria (stool in urine) are the classic tells of a colovesical fistula — an abnormal connection between the inflamed colon and the bladder. They are specific history questions worth asking when a fistulizing complication is on the table.\n\nWhy not — An uncomplicated diverticular abscess: An abscess causes a tender mass and fever, not air and stool in the urine.  A simple urinary tract infection: A plain UTI causes dysuria and frequency, not stool or air passing in the urine.  A free perforation with peritonitis: Free perforation produces diffuse peritonitis, not selectively urinary symptoms.  Diverticular bleeding: Diverticular bleeding produces hematochezia/melena, not pneumaturia and fecaluria.", "advanced"], ["Which feature in the diverticulitis history is MOST consistent with the typical presentation?", ["Constant left-lower-quadrant pain with fever and chills", "Sudden painless large-volume rectal bleeding", "Right-upper-quadrant pain radiating to the scapula", "Burning epigastric pain relieved by food", "Crampy periumbilical pain migrating to the right-lower quadrant"], 0, "Diverticulitis classically presents as constant LLQ pain with low-grade fever (the sigmoid colon is the usual site in Western patients). Painless bleeding is diverticulOSIS, not diverticulITIS — the osis/itis split the course flags repeatedly.\n\nWhy not — Sudden painless large-volume rectal bleeding: Painless large-volume bleeding describes diverticulOSIS, not the inflammatory diverticulITIS.  Right-upper-quadrant pain radiating to the scapula: RUQ pain to the scapula suggests biliary disease, not sigmoid diverticulitis.  Burning epigastric pain relieved by food: Epigastric burning relieved by food is the peptic-ulcer pattern.  Crampy periumbilical pain migrating to the right-lower quadrant: Periumbilical-to-RLQ migration is the classic appendicitis history.", "basic"], ["Moljo defends the modern view that, in a patient with diverticular disease, you do NOT need to advise avoiding:", ["Nuts, seeds, corn, and popcorn", "Red meat eaten six or more times weekly", "A chronically low-fiber diet", "Heavy alcohol use", "A sedentary lifestyle"], 0, "The seeds/nuts/corn/popcorn restriction is a debunked myth — these foods are not associated with increased diverticulitis risk, and Moljo defended this point repeatedly. The real dietary risk is red meat (≥6 servings/week) plus a low-fiber diet.\n\nWhy not — Red meat eaten six or more times weekly: High red-meat intake (≥6 servings/week) IS a genuine risk factor to counsel against.  A chronically low-fiber diet: A low-fiber diet is a real risk factor and should be corrected.  Heavy alcohol use: Heavy alcohol use is associated with diverticulitis and is worth limiting.  A sedentary lifestyle: A sedentary lifestyle raises risk; physical activity is protective.", "advanced"], ["When a woman presents with LLQ pain, why does Moljo argue the declined pelvic exam still matters?", ["Ovarian and uterine pathology can mimic the colonic source", "It is required before ordering any CT scan", "It establishes the modified Hinchey stage", "It is the only way to detect a colovesical fistula", "It rules out an upper-GI bleeding source"], 0, "Anatomy-first reasoning means the LLQ pain could arise from the ovary or uterus, not the colon. A bimanual exam can localize the pain to a pelvic structure and detect cervical motion tenderness (PID) — which is exactly why declining it leaves a gap.\n\nWhy not — It is required before ordering any CT scan: A pelvic exam is not a prerequisite for ordering CT imaging.  It establishes the modified Hinchey stage: Hinchey staging comes from CT findings, not a pelvic exam.  It is the only way to detect a colovesical fistula: Pneumaturia and fecaluria, not the pelvic exam, are the colovesical-fistula clues.  It rules out an upper-GI bleeding source: A pelvic exam says nothing about an upper-GI source.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe which tests are necessary to distinguish between the differential diagnoses in a patient with diverticulitis", [["The imaging study of choice for confirming acute diverticulitis is:", ["CT abdomen/pelvis with oral and IV contrast", "Abdominal and pelvic ultrasound", "MRI of the abdomen and pelvis", "Supine and upright abdominal radiographs", "Colonoscopy during the acute attack"], 0, "CT of the abdomen and pelvis with oral and IV contrast is the study of choice — sensitivity 94%, specificity 99% — and it both confirms the diagnosis and stages complications. Ultrasound is operator-dependent and inferior; MRI avoids radiation but is slower and costlier.\n\nWhy not — Abdominal and pelvic ultrasound: Ultrasound is easy but operator-dependent and less reliable for diverticulitis.  MRI of the abdomen and pelvis: MRI works and spares radiation but is slower, costlier, and lacks the validated CT criteria.  Supine and upright abdominal radiographs: Plain films screen for free air and obstruction but cannot confirm diverticulitis.  Colonoscopy during the acute attack: Colonoscopy is contraindicated during the acute attack (risk of perforation).", "basic"], ["The sensitivity and specificity of abdominal/pelvic CT for acute diverticulitis are approximately:", ["94% sensitivity and 99% specificity", "99% sensitivity and 94% specificity", "75% sensitivity and 80% specificity", "60% sensitivity and 70% specificity", "50% sensitivity and 50% specificity"], 0, "Moljo recited these explicitly: CT sensitivity is 94% and specificity is 99% for acute diverticulitis. The high specificity is what makes a positive CT confirmatory.\n\nWhy not — 99% sensitivity and 94% specificity: The figures are reversed — sensitivity 94, specificity 99, not the other way around.  75% sensitivity and 80% specificity: These understate CT's accuracy for diverticulitis.  60% sensitivity and 70% specificity: 60/70 are far below CT's actual performance here.  50% sensitivity and 50% specificity: Coin-flip accuracy would not make CT the study of choice.", "basic"], ["Perforation is suspected, so a contrast study is being considered. The correct contrast choice is:", ["A water-soluble medium, because leaked barium causes peritonitis", "Barium, because it gives superior mucosal detail", "Barium, because it is absorbed if it leaks", "No contrast at all, because contrast is always unsafe here", "A water-soluble medium, because barium is too costly"], 0, "When perforation is possible, use a water-soluble medium: if it leaks into the peritoneum it is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes severe barium peritonitis. Moljo emphasized this — barium leak is \"very big trouble.\"\n\nWhy not — Barium, because it gives superior mucosal detail: Barium's detail advantage is irrelevant when a leak would cause peritonitis.  Barium, because it is absorbed if it leaks: It is backwards: water-soluble contrast is absorbed; barium is not and causes peritonitis.  No contrast at all, because contrast is always unsafe here: Contrast is not categorically unsafe — the water-soluble medium is safe.  A water-soluble medium, because barium is too costly: Cost is not the reason; the reason is barium peritonitis risk on perforation.", "basic"], ["On CT, which combination of findings is most suggestive of acute diverticulitis?", ["Bowel-wall thickening >4 mm, pericolonic fat stranding, and diverticula", "Diffuse small-bowel dilation with multiple air-fluid levels", "A thickened gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fluid", "Free air under the diaphragm as the only finding", "Target-sign appendiceal wall thickening in the right lower quadrant"], 0, "The CT triad for diverticulitis is localized bowel-wall thickening (>4 mm), pericolonic fat stranding from inflammation, and the presence of colonic diverticula. Isolated free air points to perforation; the others describe different organs.\n\nWhy not — Diffuse small-bowel dilation with multiple air-fluid levels: Diffuse small-bowel dilation with air-fluid levels is an obstruction/ileus pattern.  A thickened gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fluid: Gallbladder-wall thickening with pericholecystic fluid is cholecystitis.  Free air under the diaphragm as the only finding: Isolated free air signals perforation, not uncomplicated diverticulitis.  Target-sign appendiceal wall thickening in the right lower quadrant: Appendiceal wall thickening with a target sign is appendicitis.", "basic"], ["A woman of reproductive age is being worked up for possible diverticulitis before contrast CT. Which two tests does Moljo specifically tie to giving contrast safely?", ["Renal function on the CMP and HCG", "C-reactive protein and erythrocyte sedimentation rate", "Blood cultures and a complete blood count", "Liver function tests and a lipase", "Urinalysis and a stool guaiac"], 0, "Before IV contrast you confirm adequate renal function (CMP) — \"if we need to use contrast we need to make sure the renal function is good\" — and in a woman of childbearing age you check an HCG. CRP/ESR gauge inflammation but do not gate contrast.\n\nWhy not — C-reactive protein and erythrocyte sedimentation rate: CRP/ESR mark inflammation but neither gates the safety of giving contrast.  Blood cultures and a complete blood count: Blood cultures and CBC assess bacteremia and infection, not contrast safety.  Liver function tests and a lipase: LFTs and lipase help other differentials, not contrast clearance or pregnancy.  Urinalysis and a stool guaiac: Urinalysis and guaiac address UTI and bleeding, not contrast safety.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Describe the clinical presentation and management of diverticulosis versus diverticulitis", [["A colonic diverticulum is correctly described as a PSEUDOdiverticulum because it:", ["Herniates mucosa and submucosa, not all wall layers", "Contains all layers of the colonic wall, including muscularis", "Is a congenital outpouching present from birth", "Forms only after an episode of acute inflammation", "Is a true diverticulum lined by gastric-type mucosa"], 0, "A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum: mucosa and submucosa herniate through weak points in the muscular wall (often where vessels penetrate), so it does NOT contain all the colonic layers. A true diverticulum would include the full wall.\n\nWhy not — Contains all layers of the colonic wall, including muscularis: If it contained all wall layers it would be a true diverticulum, not a pseudodiverticulum.  Is a congenital outpouching present from birth: Most Western colonic diverticula are acquired, not congenital.  Forms only after an episode of acute inflammation: Diverticula precede and predispose to inflammation; they are not caused by it.  Is a true diverticulum lined by gastric-type mucosa: Gastric-type lining describes a Meckel diverticulum, not a colonic pseudodiverticulum.", "advanced"], ["Which statement correctly separates diverticulOSIS from diverticulITIS?", ["Diverticulosis is diverticula present; diverticulitis is them inflamed", "Diverticulosis is inflamed diverticula; diverticulitis is uninflamed pouches", "Diverticulosis always causes pain; diverticulitis is always painless", "Diverticulosis requires surgery; diverticulitis is observed", "Diverticulosis is congenital; diverticulitis is always acquired"], 0, "DiverticulOSIS is simply the presence of diverticula (often asymptomatic); diverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which can be uncomplicated or complicated. This osis/itis hinge is the course-flagged distinction — and the painless-bleed counterpart lives in the endoscopy lecture.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulosis is inflamed diverticula; diverticulitis is uninflamed pouches: This reverses the two terms.  Diverticulosis always causes pain; diverticulitis is always painless: Diverticulosis is frequently asymptomatic; diverticulitis is the painful one.  Diverticulosis requires surgery; diverticulitis is observed: Most diverticulitis is managed medically; diverticulosis needs only risk-factor modification.  Diverticulosis is congenital; diverticulitis is always acquired: Western diverticula are usually acquired; the congenital note applies to proximal Asian disease.", "basic"], ["In Western countries, diverticulosis is most prevalent in the LEFT colon. Which population is noted for predominantly PROXIMAL (right-sided) disease that is often congenital?", ["Asian people and Pacific Islanders", "Northern Europeans", "Patients with chronic NSAID use", "Patients with inflammatory bowel disease", "Vegans on high-fiber diets"], 0, "Asian people and Pacific Islanders have increased odds of proximal (right-sided) diverticulosis that is often congenital — Moljo confirmed this with a student's report of right-sided disease on a rotation in Asia. Western disease is predominantly left-sided/sigmoid.\n\nWhy not — Northern Europeans: Northern Europeans follow the Western left-sided pattern.  Patients with chronic NSAID use: NSAIDs raise bleeding/perforation risk but do not shift diverticula to the right colon.  Patients with inflammatory bowel disease: IBD is a separate entity and does not define proximal diverticulosis.  Vegans on high-fiber diets: A high-fiber vegan diet is protective; it does not relocate diverticula proximally.", "basic"], ["How does the prevalence of diverticulOSIS change across the adult lifespan in the United States?", ["Under 20% at 40, ~60% by age 60", "About 60% at 40, falling to under 20%", "Stays near 50% across all adult ages", "Essentially absent until after age 70", "Peaks in the twenties, then declines thereafter"], 0, "US diverticulosis prevalence climbs steeply with age — from fewer than 20% at age 40 to roughly 60% by age 60 — and the number and size of diverticula increase as well. It is fundamentally a disease of aging.\n\nWhy not — About 60% at 40, falling to under 20%: The trend rises with age; it does not fall.  Stays near 50% across all adult ages: Prevalence is strongly age-dependent, not flat at 50%.  Essentially absent until after age 70: Diverticula are common well before 70 and increase steadily from mid-adulthood.  Peaks in the twenties, then declines thereafter: It increases with age rather than peaking in the twenties.", "basic"]]], [4, "Describe the management of diverticulitis, its prognosis, and resultant complications", [["A reliable, immunocompetent outpatient has CT-confirmed UNCOMPLICATED diverticulitis. The most appropriate management is:", ["Low-fiber diet and analgesia, no antibiotics", "Immediate broad-spectrum IV antibiotics and admission", "Urgent sigmoid colectomy now", "CT-guided percutaneous abscess drainage", "Colonoscopy this admission to confirm diagnosis"], 0, "Selected uncomplicated outpatients are managed with a clear diet advancing to low fiber, acetaminophen and antispasmodics, and close follow-up — antibiotics are usually not required. Moljo stressed the data: \"we really don't need antibiotics for uncomplicated diverticulitis.\"\n\nWhy not — Immediate broad-spectrum IV antibiotics and admission: IV antibiotics and admission are for complicated disease or high-risk hosts, not this patient.  Urgent sigmoid colectomy now: Urgent colectomy is reserved for Hinchey III/IV or failure of medical therapy.  CT-guided percutaneous abscess drainage: Percutaneous drainage treats an abscess ≥4 cm, which uncomplicated disease lacks.  Colonoscopy this admission to confirm diagnosis: Colonoscopy is deferred to 6–8 weeks after resolution, never during the acute attack.", "advanced"], ["Antibiotics are chosen for a patient with diverticulitis and a fluoroquinolone is selected. To cover anaerobes adequately, you must add:", ["Metronidazole", "Azithromycin", "A second fluoroquinolone", "Vancomycin", "Ceftriaxone"], 0, "Fluoroquinolones and TMP-SMX do not cover anaerobes, so each must be paired with metronidazole (clindamycin if metronidazole is not tolerated). Amoxicillin-clavulanate is the single-agent alternative because it covers both aerobes and anaerobes.\n\nWhy not — Azithromycin: Azithromycin does not provide the anaerobic coverage diverticulitis requires.  A second fluoroquinolone: Adding a second fluoroquinolone still leaves the anaerobic gap unfilled.  Vancomycin: Vancomycin targets gram-positives (e.g., C. diff), not gut anaerobes here.  Ceftriaxone: Ceftriaxone covers gram-negatives but not the anaerobes; it too would need metronidazole.", "advanced"], ["CT shows a 5 cm pericolic abscess complicating diverticulitis. The most appropriate next step is:", ["CT-guided percutaneous drainage plus antibiotics", "Antibiotics alone with no drainage", "Immediate sigmoid colectomy", "Oral diet advancement and discharge", "Barium enema to define the abscess"], 0, "The 4 cm threshold decides the move: an abscess <4 cm is managed with antibiotics alone, while one ≥4 cm gets CT-guided percutaneous drainage added. At 5 cm, drain it. Surgery is reserved for drainage failure or inaccessible collections.\n\nWhy not — Antibiotics alone with no drainage: Antibiotics alone suffice only for abscesses <4 cm; this one is ≥4 cm.  Immediate sigmoid colectomy: Colectomy is for ruptured abscess, Hinchey III/IV, or failed drainage — not a first move here.  Oral diet advancement and discharge: Discharging an untreated 5 cm abscess risks rupture and peritonitis.  Barium enema to define the abscess: Barium is contraindicated when perforation is possible; CT already defines the abscess.", "basic"], ["On CT, a patient has small extraluminal air bubbles but NO oral contrast leaking outside the colon (microperforation). The expected management is:", ["IV antibiotics, with about 94% managed nonoperatively", "Emergency laparotomy for all such patients", "Discharge home on no treatment", "Percutaneous drainage of the free air", "Barium enema to confirm the leak"], 0, "Microperforation (contained — air bubbles but no extraluminal contrast) is treated initially with IV antibiotics, and roughly 94% are managed nonoperatively. That contrasts sharply with frank perforation (free air, feculent peritonitis), which mandates emergency surgery.\n\nWhy not — Emergency laparotomy for all such patients: Emergency surgery is for frank perforation with peritonitis, not contained microperforation.  Discharge home on no treatment: Microperforation still requires IV antibiotics and inpatient observation.  Percutaneous drainage of the free air: You drain a fluid abscess, not scattered air bubbles.  Barium enema to confirm the leak: Barium is contraindicated with a perforation and adds nothing over CT.", "advanced"], ["A patient recovers from a SECOND episode of acute diverticulitis. The approximate risk of a further recurrence, and the most common complication of diverticulitis overall, are:", ["About 66% recurrence; obstruction is the most common complication", "About 33% recurrence; perforation is the most common complication", "About 10% recurrence; abscess is the most common complication", "About 90% recurrence; fistula is the most common complication", "About 50% recurrence; bleeding is the most common complication"], 0, "Recurrence is 33% after a first episode and 66% after a second. Across all complications, obstruction is the most common, followed by perforation and then abscess. These two numbers and the complication ranking are high-yield exam anchors.\n\nWhy not — About 33% recurrence; perforation is the most common complication: 33% is the recurrence after the FIRST episode; after the second it is 66%.  About 10% recurrence; abscess is the most common complication: 10% understates recurrence, and abscess is not the most common complication.  About 90% recurrence; fistula is the most common complication: 90% overstates recurrence; fistula is not the leading complication.  About 50% recurrence; bleeding is the most common complication: 50% is not the quoted figure, and bleeding is not the leading complication.", "advanced"], ["A 45-year-old recovers from his first episode of diverticulitis and has never had a colonoscopy. The correct plan is to perform colonoscopy:", ["6–8 weeks after resolution, to exclude other pathology", "During the acute attack, to confirm the diagnosis", "Within 24 hours of presentation, before starting antibiotics", "Only if he ever develops painless rectal bleeding", "Never, because CT already made the diagnosis"], 0, "Colonoscopy is done 6–8 weeks AFTER the attack resolves (the slide says weeks; the transcript's \"hours\" is an ASR slip), never during the acute attack when scoping risks perforation. In a younger first-time patient it is indicated to exclude colorectal cancer or other pathology.\n\nWhy not — During the acute attack, to confirm the diagnosis: Scoping during the acute attack risks perforating the inflamed colon — it is avoided.  Within 24 hours of presentation, before starting antibiotics: There is no role for emergent colonoscopy before antibiotics in diverticulitis.  Only if he ever develops painless rectal bleeding: The post-resolution scope is to exclude cancer/other pathology, not contingent on later bleeding.  Never, because CT already made the diagnosis: CT diagnoses the attack, but colonoscopy still excludes a coexisting lesion after healing.", "advanced"]]]]]];
// QUIZ_END
